on systems|year=2006|publisher=Naval Institute|location=Annapolis, Md|isbn=1557502625|page=243|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4S3h8j_NEmkC&pg=PA243&lpg=PA243&dq=%E2%80%9CSurveillance+%26+Threat+Alert+Radar+-+STAR+-+EL/M-2238&source=bl&ots=hIYuJVVY6Y&sig=YEcLOapQWqLtbhVDrCsnHij5IZ0&hl=en&sa=X&ei=WyzoUZXVOcurrAfzwYGoDQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%E2%80%9CSurveillance%20%26%20Threat%20Alert%20Radar%20-%20STAR%20-%20EL%2FM-2238&f=false|edition=5th}}</ref>\n*''Communication:'' [[Inmarsat]],\n*''Sonar:'' 1 x hull mounted Vycheda MG-311 (NATO: Wolf Paw) sonar replaced with Bharat HUMSA during MLR, 1 x Vyega MG-325 (NATO: Mare Tail) variable depth sonar\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*''Anti-surface:''\n*4 \u00d7 [[P-15 Termit|SS-N-2D Styx AShM]] missiles\n*''Air-defence:''\n*2 \u00d7 [[S-125 Neva/Pechora#Naval version|S-125M]] (NATO: SA-N-1) [[Surface to air missile|SAM]] launchers\n*''Guns:''\n*1 \u00d7 {{convert|76.2|mm|in|abbr=on|0}} main gun,\n*4 \u00d7 [[AK-630|{{convert|30|mm|in|abbr=on|1}} AK-630M]] [[Close-in weapon system|CIWS]]\n*''Anti-submarine: ''\n*1 \u00d7 {{convert|533|mm|in|abbr=on|0}} PTA 533 quintuple [[torpedo tube]] launcher,\n*2 \u00d7 [[RBU-6000]] anti-submarine mortars,\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship aircraft=1 x [[HAL Chetak]] helicopter\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''INS ''Ranjit''''' is the third of the five {{sclass-|Rajput|destroyer}} built for the [[Indian Navy]]. ''Ranjit'' was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 15 September 1983 and remained in service till 6 May 2019, when it was decommissioned.<ref name=\"ranjit-deco\">{{cite web|url=http://pib.nic.in/PressReleseDetail.aspx?PRID=1571660&RegID=3&LID=1|title=INS Ranjit Sails into Sunset Culminating 36 years of Glorious Era\n|publisher=PIB|accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Construction and service ==\n''Ranjit'' was laid down by Indian request under the Soviet name ''Lovkiy'' at the [[61 Kommunara Shipbuilding Plant]] in [[Nikolayev, Ukraine]] on 29 June 1977 with the serial number 2203. She had previously been planned to be named ''Porazhayushchy'' on 16 May of that year, and was built as a Project 61MZ large anti-submarine ship ([[NATO reporting name]] [[Kashin-class destroyer]]). The destroyer was launched on 16 June 1979 and added to the list of ships of the [[Soviet Navy]] on 30 October 1981.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://defpost.com/indian-navy-to-decommission-its-rajput-class-destroyer-ins-ranjit-on-may-6/|title=Indian Navy to Decommission Its Rajput-Class Destroyer, INS Ranjit, on May 6|last=Releases|first=DP Press|date=2019-05-03|website=DefPost|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> \n\nShe was was commissioned on 15 September 1983 in the erstwhile USSR with then Captain Vishnu Bhagwat in command. She completed post commissioning trials and set sail from Poti in USSR on 14 November 1983 and entered Mumbai on 22 Dec 1983. She visited ports in Bulgaria, Yugoslavia and Egypt during her maiden voyage to India. She joined the Western Fleet and operated under the Flag of FOCWF till April 1999. In May 1999, she changed her home port to Vishakhapatnam to become a part of the Eastern Fleet.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lt Cdr Phani|first=Venkata|date=|title=JEET JEET RANJIT - The beginning of the end of an Era|url=https://www.indiannavy.nic.in/desa/sites/default/files/repository-document/Quarterdeck%202019.pdf|journal=Quarterdeck 2019|publisher=Directorate of Ex-Servicemen Affairs, Indian Navy, Government of India|volume=2019|pages=50-53|via=}}</ref>\n\nINS Ranjit  was decommissioned at the naval dockyard in [[Visakhapatnam]] on 6 May 2019 after serving for 36 years.<ref>{{cite web |title=INS Ranjit Decommissioned |url=https://zeenews.india.com/india/indian-navys-frontline-missile-destroyer-ins-ranjit-to-be-decommissioned-on-may-6-2200884.html |website=ZEE News |publisher=ZEE News |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref> Her last commanding officer was Captain Vikram C Mehra.<ref name=\"ranjit-deco\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{Cite journal|last=Berezhnoy|first=S.S.|date=January 1995|title=\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0412\u041c\u0424 1945-1995: \u043a\u0440\u0435\u0439\u0441\u0435\u0440\u0430, \u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438, \u044d\u0441\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0446\u044b|trans-title=Soviet Navy, 1945\u20131995: Cruisers, large anti-submarine ships, and destroyers|url=|journal=\u041c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043b\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0446\u0438\u044f [Morskaya kollektsiya]|language=Russian|volume=|issue=1|pages=|oclc=831205953|ref=harv|via=}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020204003728/http://www.bharat-rakshak.com/NAVY/Rajput.html ''Rajput'' class at Bharat-Rakshak.com]\n\n[[File:INS Ranjit (D53).jpg|thumb|300px|left| INS ''Ranjit'']]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ranjit (D53)}}\n[[Category:Rajput-class destroyers]]\n[[Category:Ships built in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:1979 ships]]\n\n\n{{Destroyers_of_the_Indian_Navy}}{{Kashin-class destroyer}}{{India-mil-stub}}\n{{Mil-ship-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/INS_Ranjit_(D53)"}
{"title_page": "Inguinal hernia surgery", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical intervention\n| name         = Inguinal hernia surgery\n| synonym      =\n| image        = File:Right Inguinal Hernia.JPG|thumb|\n| caption      = Open surgical repair of a right inguinal hernia\n| alt          = \n| pronounce    = \n| specialty    =gastroenterology\n| synonyms     = \n| ICD10        = \n| ICD9         = \n| ICD9unlinked = \n| CPT          = \n| MeshID       = \n| LOINC        = \n| other_codes  = \n| MedlinePlus  = \n| eMedicine    = \n}}\n'''Inguinal hernia surgery''' is an operation to repair a weakness in the abdominal wall that abnormally allows abdominal contents to slip into a narrow tube called the [[inguinal canal]] in the groin region.\n\nSurgery remains the ultimate treatment for all types of [[hernia]]s as they will not get better on their own, however not all require immediate repair.<ref name=\":022\">{{Cite journal|last=Hewitt|first=D. Brock|date=2017-06-27|title=Groin Hernia|journal=JAMA|language=en|volume=317|issue=24|pages=2560|doi=10.1001/jama.2017.1556|pmid=28655018|issn=0098-7484}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uptodate.com/contents/overview-of-treatment-for-inguinal-and-femoral-hernia-in-adults|title=Overview of treatment for inguinal and femoral hernia in adults|website=www.uptodate.com|access-date=2017-12-14}}</ref> [[Elective surgery]] is offered to most patients taking into account their level of pain, discomfort, degree of disruption in normal activity, as well as their overall level of health.<ref name=\":022\"/> Emergency surgery is typically reserved for patients with life-threatening complications of inguinal hernias such as incarceration and strangulation. Incarceration occurs when [[Omentum majus|intra-abdominal fat]] or small intestine becomes stuck within the canal and cannot slide back into the abdominal cavity either on its own or with [https://emedicine.medscape.com/article/149608-overview?pa=UCBfUUoaBP5LbLkWxNmauKNaMqsTHK4LIi1LCKQSyEuIsCDkyLIA2tdvTZW%2FxVe2TUftft%2BgTNVmHRP6HGZguSchrzF%2F7vlnSF6AEX%2F09M8%3D manual maneuvers]. Left untreated, incarceration may progress to bowel strangulation as a result of restricted blood supply to the trapped segment of small intestine causing that portion to die.<ref name=\":222\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.niddk.nih.gov/health-information/digestive-diseases/inguinal-hernia|title=Inguinal Hernia {{!}} NIDDK|work=National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Successful outcomes of repair are usually measured via rates of hernia recurrence, pain and subsequent quality of life.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.europeanherniasociety.eu/sites/www.europeanherniasociety.eu/files/medias/PDF/HerniaSurgeGuidelinesStatementsRecomendations.pdf|title=World Guidelines for Hernia Management|website=European Hernia Society|access-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSurgical repair of inguinal hernias is one of the most commonly performed operations worldwide and the most commonly performed surgery within the United States. A combined 20 million cases of both inguinal and [[femoral hernia]] repair are performed every year around the world with 800,000 cases in the US as of 2003. The UK reports around 70,000 cases performed every year.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ta83/chapter/6-Implications-for-the-NHS|title=Laparoscopic surgery for inguinal hernia repair {{!}} Guidance and guidelines {{!}} NICE|website=www.nice.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-12-05}}</ref> Groin hernias account for almost 75% of all abdominal wall hernias with the lifetime risk of an inguinal hernia in men and women being 27% and 3% respectively. Men account for nearly 90% of all repairs performed and have a [[Multimodal distribution|bimodal incidence]] of inguinal hernias peaking at 1 year of age and again in those over the age of 40. Although women account for roughly 70% of femoral hernia repairs, indirect inguinal hernias are still the most common subtype of groin hernia in both males and females.<ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://accesssurgery.mhmedical.com/content.aspx?aid=1117751838|title=Schwartz's Principles of Surgery|last=P. Wagner|first=Justin|last2=Brunicardi|first2=F. Charles|last3=Amid|first3=Parviz K.|last4=Chen|first4=David C.|date=2014|publisher=McGraw-Hill Education|editor-last=Brunicardi|editor-first=F. Charles|edition=10|location=New York, NY|editor-last2=Andersen|editor-first2=Dana K.|editor-last3=Billiar|editor-first3=Timothy R.|editor-last4=Dunn|editor-first4=David L.|editor-last5=Hunter|editor-first5=John G.|editor-last6=Matthews|editor-first6=Jeffrey B.|editor-last7=Pollock|editor-first7=Raphael E.|chapter=Inguinal Hernias}}</ref>\n\n== Indications for surgery ==\nSociety guidelines recommend that indications for surgery take into account the severity of symptoms, the type of hernia, previous surgeries, hernia size, bowel incarceration (bowel can no longer return to the abdomen) and the overall general health of the person.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":022\"/><ref name=\":422\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.sages.org/publications/patient-information/patient-information-for-laparoscopic-inguinal-hernia-repair-from-sages/|title=Inguinal Hernia Repair Surgery Information from SAGES|work=SAGES|access-date=2017-12-05|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ta83/chapter/2-Clinical-need-and-practice|title=Laparoscopic surgery for inguinal hernia repair {{!}} Guidance and guidelines {{!}} NICE|website=www.nice.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-12-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Non-urgent repair ===\n[[Elective surgery]] is planned in order to help relieve symptoms, respect the person's preference, and prevent future complications that may require emergency surgery.<ref name=\":5\">DynaMed Plus [Internet]. Ipswich (MA): EBSCO Information Services. 1995 - . Record No. 113880, Groin hernia in adults and adolescents; [updated 2017 Nov 27, cited '''Nov 27, 2017''']; [about 28 screens]. Available from <nowiki>http://www.dynamed.com/login.aspx?direct=true&site=DynaMed&id=113880</nowiki>. Registration and login required.</ref><ref name=\":03\"/>\n\nSurgery is offered to the majority of people who:\n* have symptoms that interfere with their normal level of activity.<ref name=\":422\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n* have hernias that become increasingly difficult to reduce.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":422\" />\n* are female as it is often difficult to classify the subtype of hernia based on an exam alone.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":422\" />\nSymptomatic hernias tend to cause pain or discomfort within the groin region that may increase with exertion and improve with rest. A swollen scrotum within males may coincide with persistent feelings of heaviness or generalized lower abdominal discomfort. The sensation of groin pressure tends to be most prominent at the end of the day as well as after strenuous activities. Changes in sensation may be experienced along the scrotum and inner thigh.<ref name=\":622\">{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://accesssurgery.mhmedical.com/content.aspx?bookid=980&sectionid=59610879#1117751668|title=Schwartz's Principles of Surgery, 10e|last=Wagner|first=Justin|last2=Brunicardi|last3=Amid|last4=Chen|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=2015|isbn=978-0-07179674-3|location=New York, NY|pages=|chapter=Inguinal Hernias}}</ref>\n\n=== Urgent repair ===\nA hernia in which the small intestine has become incarcerated or strangulated constitutes a surgical emergency. Symptoms include:<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":222\"/><ref name=\":622\"/>\n* Fever\n* Nausea and vomiting\n* Extreme pain in the area of the hernia\n* Warm hernia bulge with surrounding skin redness\n* Can no longer pass gas or stool\nSurgical repair within 6 hours of the above symptoms may be able to save the strangulated portion of intestine.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Contraindications to surgery ==\nThe person with the hernia should be given an opportunity to participate in the [[Shared decision-making in medicine|shared decision-making]] with their physicians as almost all procedures carry significant risks. The benefits of inguinal hernia repair can become overshadowed by risks such that elective repair is no longer in a person's best interest. Such cases include:<ref name=\":622\"/><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n* People [[ASA physical status classification system|with unstable medical conditions]]\n* Repair using mesh is withheld if a person has an active infection within the groin or [[Bacteremia|within the blood stream]]\n* Elective repair is delayed in pregnant women until 4 weeks after delivery\nAdditionally, certain medical conditions can prevent people from being candidates for laparoscopic approaches to repair. Examples of such include:<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n* People who are unable to undergo general anesthesia\n* Prior major open abdominal surgery\n* People who have [[ascites]]\n* Previous radiation therapy to the pelvis\n* A complex hernia\n\n== Surgical approaches ==\nTechniques to repair inguinal hernias fall into two broad categories termed \"open\" and \"[[Laparoscopic surgery|laparoscopic]]\". Surgeons tailor their approach by taking into account factors such as their own experience with either techniques, the features of the hernia itself, and the person's anesthetic needs.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":622\"/>\n\nThe cost associated with either approach varies widely across regions. As an example the UK's [[National Health Service|NHS]] spends \u00a356 million a year in repairing inguinal hernias 96% of which were repaired via the open mesh approach while only 4% were done laparoscopically.<ref name=\":7\" /> Updated guidelines published by the International Endohernia Society cast doubt on the comprehensiveness of cost comparison studies due in part to the complexity inherent in calculating costs across institutions.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}} The IES asserts that hospital and societal costs are in fact lower for laparoscopic repairs as compared to open approaches. They recommend the routine use of reusable instruments as well as improving the proficiency of surgeons to help further decrease costs as well as time spent in the OR.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bittner|first=R.|last2=Montgomery|first2=M. A.|last3=Arregui|first3=E.|last4=Bansal|first4=V.|last5=Bingener|first5=J.|last6=Bisgaard|first6=T.|last7=Buhck|first7=H.|last8=Dudai|first8=M.|last9=Ferzli|first9=G. S.|date=2015|title=Update of guidelines on laparoscopic (TAPP) and endoscopic (TEP) treatment of inguinal hernia (International Endohernia Society)|journal=Surgical Endoscopy|volume=29|issue=2|pages=289\u2013321|doi=10.1007/s00464-014-3917-8|issn=0930-2794|pmc=4293469|pmid=25398194}}</ref>\n\n=== Open hernia repair ===\nAll techniques involve an approximate 10-cm incision in the groin. Once exposed, the hernia sac is returned to the abdominal cavity  or excised and the abdominal wall is very often reinforced with [[Surgical mesh|mesh]].<ref name=\":222\"/> There are many techniques that do not utilize mesh and have their own situations where they are preferable.<ref name=\":22\"/><ref name=\":422\"/>\n\nOpen repairs are classified via whether prosthetic mesh is utilized or whether the patient's own tissue is used to repair the weakness. Prosthetic repairs enable surgeons to repair a hernia without causing undue tension in the surrounding tissues while reinforcing the abdominal wall. Repairs with undue tension have been shown to increase the likelihood that the hernia will recur. Repairs not using prosthetic mesh are preferable options in patients with an above-average risk of infection such as cases where the bowel has become strangulated (blood supply lost due to constriction).<ref name=\":622\"/>\n\nOne large benefit of this approach lies in its ability to tailor anesthesia to a person's needs. People can be administered [[local anesthesia]], a [[Spinal anaesthesia|spinal block]], as well as [[General anaesthesia|general anesthesia]].<ref name=\":5\" /> Local anesthesia has been shown to cause less pain after surgery, shorten operating times, shorten recovery times as well as decrease the need to return to the hospital. However, people who undergo general anesthesia tend to be able to go home faster and experience fewer complications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nordin|first=P\u00e4r|last2=Zetterstr\u00f6m|first2=Henrik|last3=Gunnarsson|first3=Ulf|last4=Nilsson|first4=Erik|date=2003-09-13|title=Local, regional, or general anaesthesia in groin hernia repair: multicentre randomised trial|journal=Lancet|volume=362|issue=9387|pages=853\u2013858|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(03)14339-5|issn=1474-547X|pmid=13678971}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=van Veen|first=Ruben N.|last2=Mahabier|first2=Chander|last3=Dawson|first3=Imro|last4=Hop|first4=Wim C.|last5=Kok|first5=Niels F. M.|last6=Lange|first6=Johan F.|last7=Jeekel|first7=Johannus|date=March 2008|title=Spinal or local anesthesia in lichtenstein hernia repair: a randomized controlled trial|journal=Annals of Surgery|volume=247|issue=3|pages=428\u2013433|doi=10.1097/SLA.0b013e318165b0ff|issn=0003-4932|pmid=18376185}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> The European Hernia Society recommends the use of local anesthesia particularly for people with ongoing medical conditions.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== Open mesh repairs ====\n[[File:Hernia mesh 1.jpg|thumb|Polypropylene mesh used for inguinal hernia surgery]]\n[[File:Inguinal Hernia Patch.png|thumb|Inguinal Hernia Patch. Animation in the reference.]]\n\nRepairs that utilize mesh are usually the first recommendation for the vast majority of patients including those that undergo laparoscopic repair.<ref name=\":3\" /> Procedures that employ mesh are the most commonly performed as they have been able to demonstrate greater results as compared to non-mesh repairs.<ref name=\":622\"/> Approaches utilizing mesh have been able to demonstrate faster return to usual activity, lower rates of persistent pain, shorter hospital stays, and a lower likelihood that the hernia will recur.<ref name=\"Scott 2002 CD002197\">{{Cite journal|last=Scott|first=N. W.|last2=McCormack|first2=K.|last3=Graham|first3=P.|last4=Go|first4=P. M.|last5=Ross|first5=S. J.|last6=Grant|first6=A. M.|date=2002|title=Open mesh versus non-mesh for repair of femoral and inguinal hernia|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|issue=4|pages=CD002197|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD002197|issn=1469-493X|pmid=12519568|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/7dfaf6207dca8eb11e07e53f702a61104e60fbeb}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rosenberg|first=Jacob|last2=Bisgaard|first2=Thue|last3=Kehlet|first3=Henrik|last4=Wara|first4=P\u00e5l|last5=Asmussen|first5=Torsten|last6=Juul|first6=Poul|last7=Strand|first7=Lasse|last8=Andersen|first8=Finn Heidmann|last9=Bay-Nielsen|first9=Morten|date=February 2011|title=Danish Hernia Database recommendations for the management of inguinal and femoral hernia in adults|journal=Danish Medical Bulletin|volume=58|issue=2|pages=C4243|issn=1603-9629|pmid=21299930}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bay-Nielsen|first=M.|last2=Kehlet|first2=H.|last3=Strand|first3=L.|last4=Malmstr\u00f8m|first4=J.|last5=Andersen|first5=F. H.|last6=Wara|first6=P.|last7=Juul|first7=P.|last8=Callesen|first8=T.|last9=Danish Hernia Database Collaboration|date=2001-10-06|title=Quality assessment of 26,304 herniorrhaphies in Denmark: a prospective nationwide study|journal=Lancet|volume=358|issue=9288|pages=1124\u20131128|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(01)06251-1|issn=0140-6736|pmid=11597665}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Matthews|first=Richard D.|last2=Anthony|first2=Thomas|last3=Kim|first3=Lawrence T.|last4=Wang|first4=Jia|last5=Fitzgibbons|first5=Robert J.|last6=Giobbie-Hurder|first6=Anita|last7=Reda|first7=Domenic J.|last8=Itani|first8=Kamal M. F.|last9=Neumayer|first9=Leigh A.|date=November 2007|title=Factors associated with postoperative complications and hernia recurrence for patients undergoing inguinal hernia repair: a report from the VA Cooperative Hernia Study Group|journal=American Journal of Surgery|volume=194|issue=5|pages=611\u2013617|doi=10.1016/j.amjsurg.2007.07.018|issn=1879-1883|pmid=17936422}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=EU Hernia Trialists Collaboration|date=March 2002|title=Repair of groin hernia with synthetic mesh: meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials|journal=Annals of Surgery|volume=235|issue=3|pages=322\u2013332|issn=0003-4932|pmc=1422456|pmid=11882753|doi=10.1097/00000658-200203000-00003}}</ref>\n\nOptions for mesh include either [[Surgical mesh|synthetic]] or [[Biomesh|biologic]]. Synthetic mesh provides the option of using \"heavyweight\" as well as \"lightweight\" variations according to the diameter and number of mesh fibers.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Earle|first=David B.|last2=Mark|first2=Lisa A.|date=February 2008|title=Prosthetic material in inguinal hernia repair: how do I choose?|journal=The Surgical Clinics of North America|volume=88|issue=1|pages=179\u2013201, x|doi=10.1016/j.suc.2007.11.002|issn=0039-6109|pmid=18267169}}</ref> Lightweight mesh has been shown to have fewer complications related to the mesh itself than its heavyweight counterparts.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bittner|first=R.|last2=Arregui|first2=M. E.|last3=Bisgaard|first3=T.|last4=Dudai|first4=M.|last5=Ferzli|first5=G. S.|last6=Fitzgibbons|first6=R. J.|last7=Fortelny|first7=R. H.|last8=Klinge|first8=U.|last9=Kockerling|first9=F.|date=September 2011|title=Guidelines for laparoscopic (TAPP) and endoscopic (TEP) treatment of inguinal hernia [International Endohernia Society (IEHS)]|journal=Surgical Endoscopy|volume=25|issue=9|pages=2773\u20132843|doi=10.1007/s00464-011-1799-6|issn=1432-2218|pmc=3160575|pmid=21751060}}</ref> It was additionally correlated with lower rates of chronic pain while sharing the same rates of hernia recurrence as compared to heavyweight options.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sajid|first=Muhammad S.|last2=Kalra|first2=Lorain|last3=Parampalli|first3=Umesh|last4=Sains|first4=Parv S.|last5=Baig|first5=Mirza K.|date=June 2013|title=A systematic review and meta-analysis evaluating the effectiveness of lightweight mesh against heavyweight mesh in influencing the incidence of chronic groin pain following laparoscopic inguinal hernia repair|journal=American Journal of Surgery|volume=205|issue=6|pages=726\u2013736|doi=10.1016/j.amjsurg.2012.07.046|issn=1879-1883|pmid=23561639}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sajid|first=M. S.|last2=Leaver|first2=C.|last3=Baig|first3=M. K.|last4=Sains|first4=P.|date=January 2012|title=Systematic review and meta-analysis of the use of lightweight versus heavyweight mesh in open inguinal hernia repair|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=99|issue=1|pages=29\u201337|doi=10.1002/bjs.7718|issn=1365-2168|pmid=22038579}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bittner|first=R.|last2=Montgomery|first2=M. A.|last3=Arregui|first3=E.|last4=Bansal|first4=V.|last5=Bingener|first5=J.|last6=Bisgaard|first6=T.|last7=Buhck|first7=H.|last8=Dudai|first8=M.|last9=Ferzli|first9=G. S.|date=2015-02-01|title=Update of guidelines on laparoscopic (TAPP) and endoscopic (TEP) treatment of inguinal hernia (International Endohernia Society)|journal=Surgical Endoscopy|language=en|volume=29|issue=2|pages=289\u2013321|doi=10.1007/s00464-014-3917-8|pmid=25398194|pmc=4293469|issn=0930-2794}}</ref> This has led to the adoption of lightweight mesh for minimizing the chance of chronic pain after surgery.<ref name=\":622\"/> Biologic mesh is indicated in cases where the risk of infection is a major concern such as cases in which the bowel has become strangulated. They tend to have lower [[Ultimate tensile strength|tensile strength]] than their synthetic counterparts lending them to higher rates of mesh rupture.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Smart|first=Neil J.|last2=Bloor|first2=Stephen|date=September 2012|title=Durability of biologic implants for use in hernia repair: a review|journal=Surgical Innovation|volume=19|issue=3|pages=221\u2013229|doi=10.1177/1553350611429027|issn=1553-3514|pmid=22143748}}</ref>\n\nBiomeshes are increasingly popular since their first use in 1999<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Edelman|first1=DS|last2=Hodde|first2=JP|year=2006|title=Bioactive prosthetic material for treatment of hernias|journal=Surgical Technology International|volume=15|pages=104\u20138|pmid=17029169}}</ref> and their subsequent introduction on the market in 2003. Some meshes have a price comparable to the high end of synthetic meshes, the cheapest ($500) being Surgisis-Biodesign, manufactured by [[Cook Group]], made from the [[extra cellular matrix]] of pig [[small intestinal submucosa]].<ref>Inguinal Hernia Repair with Biodesign\u00ae (Surgisis\u00ae) -- David Edelman, MD [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zieBX96y0rQ]{{Unreliable medical source|date=January 2012}}</ref> Currently, there exists one synthetic totally absorbable mesh, Tigr Matrix, manufactured by [[Novus Scientific]], on the US market (510(k) [[Food and Drug Administration]] clearance)<ref>http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/cdrh_docs/pdf9/K092224.pdf{{full citation needed|date=November 2012}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> since 2010 and on the EU market since 2011. It only has one 3-year [[Clinical trial#Pre-clinical studies|pre-clinical evidence]] on [[sheep]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hjort|first1=H.|last2=Mathisen|first2=T.|last3=Alves|first3=A.|last4=Clermont|first4=G.|last5=Boutrand|first5=J. P.|year=2011|title=Three-year results from a preclinical implantation study of a long-term resorbable surgical mesh with time-dependent mechanical characteristics|journal=Hernia|volume=16|issue=2|pages=191\u20137|doi=10.1007/s10029-011-0885-y|pmc=3895198|pmid=21972049}}</ref>\n\nMeshes made of [[mosquito net]] cloth, in [[copolymer]] of [[polyethylene]] and [[polypropylene]] have been used for low-income patients in rural [[India]] and [[Ghana]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=M. G.|last2=Oppong|first2=C.|last3=Simmermacher|first3=R.|last4=Park|first4=K.|last5=Kurzer|first5=M.|last6=Vanotoo|first6=L.|last7=Kingsnorth|first7=A. N.|year=2008|title=The use of sterilised polyester mosquito net mesh for inguinal hernia repair in Ghana|journal=Hernia|volume=13|issue=2|pages=155\u20139|doi=10.1007/s10029-008-0460-3|pmid=19089526}}</ref> Each piece costs $0.01, 3700 times cheaper than an equivalent commercial mesh.<ref name=\"Tongaonkar03\">{{cite journal|last1=Tongaonkar|first1=Ravindranath R.|last2=Reddy|first2=Brahma V.|last3=Mehta|first3=Virendra K.|last4=Singh|first4=Ningthoujam Somorjit|last5=Shivade|first5=Sanjay|year=2003|title=Preliminary Multicentric Trial of Cheap Indigenous Mosquito-Net Cloth for Tension-free Hernia Repair|url=http://www.bioline.org.br/request?is03018|journal=Indian Journal of Surgery|volume=65|issue=1|pages=89\u201395}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wilhelm|first1=T.J.|last2=Freudenberg|first2=S.|last3=Jonas|first3=E.|last4=Grobholz|first4=R.|last5=Post|first5=S.|last6=Kyamanywa|first6=P.|year=2007|title=Sterilized Mosquito Net versus Commercial Mesh for Hernia Repair|journal=European Surgical Research|volume=39|issue=5|pages=312\u20137|doi=10.1159/000104402|pmid=17595545}}</ref> They give results identical to commercial meshes in terms of infection and recurrence rate at 5 years.<ref name=\"Tongaonkar03\" />\n\n===== Lichtenstein technique =====\nThe Lichtenstein tension-free repair has persisted as one of the most commonly performed procedures in the world. The European Hernia Society recommends that in cases where an open approach is indicated, the Lichtenstein technique be utilized as the preferred method.<ref name=\":3\" /> Recent studies have indicated that mesh attachment with the use of [[Butyl cyanoacrylate|adhesive glue]] is faster and less likely to cause post-op pain as compared to attachment via suture material.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sun|first=Ping|last2=Cheng|first2=Xiang|last3=Deng|first3=Shichang|last4=Hu|first4=Qinggang|last5=Sun|first5=Yi|last6=Zheng|first6=Qichang|date=7 Feb 2017|title=Mesh fixation with glue versus suture for chronic pain and recurrence in Lichtenstein inguinal hernioplasty|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=2|pages=CD010814|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD010814.pub2|issn=1469-493X|pmid=28170080|pmc=6464532}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=de Goede|first=B.|last2=Klitsie|first2=P. J.|last3=van Kempen|first3=B. J. H.|last4=Timmermans|first4=L.|last5=Jeekel|first5=J.|last6=Kazemier|first6=G.|last7=Lange|first7=J. F.|date=May 2013|title=Meta-analysis of glue versus sutured mesh fixation for Lichtenstein inguinal hernia repair|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=100|issue=6|pages=735\u2013742|doi=10.1002/bjs.9072|issn=1365-2168|pmid=23436683}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shen|first=Ying-mo|last2=Sun|first2=Wen-bing|last3=Chen|first3=Jie|last4=Liu|first4=Su-jun|last5=Wang|first5=Ming-gang|date=April 2012|title=NBCA medical adhesive (n-butyl-2-cyanoacrylate) versus suture for patch fixation in Lichtenstein inguinal herniorrhaphy: a randomized controlled trial|journal=Surgery|volume=151|issue=4|pages=550\u2013555|doi=10.1016/j.surg.2011.09.031|issn=1532-7361|pmid=22088820}}</ref>\n\n===== Plug and patch technique =====\nThe plug and patch tension-free technique has fallen out of favor due to higher rates of mesh shift along with its tendency to irritate surrounding tissue. This has led to the European Hernia Society recommending that the technique not be used in most cases.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n===== Other open mesh repair techniques =====\nA variety of other tension-free techniques have been developed and include:<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":622\"/>\n* Prolene mesh system (PHS)\n* Kugel (preperitoneal repair)<ref>[https://jomi.com/article/8/minimally-invasive-open-inguinal-hernia-repair] Reinhorn M. Minimally invasive open preperitoneal inguinal hernia repair. J Med Ins. 2014;2014(8). doi:https://doi.org/10.24296/jomi/8</ref>\n* Stoppa\n* Trabucco (Hertra mesh)\n* Wantz\n* Rutkow/Robbins\n* Modified APP\n\n==== Open non-mesh repairs ====\nTechniques in which mesh is not used are referred to as tissue repair technique, suture technique, and tension technique. All involve bringing together the tissue with sutures and are a viable alternative when mesh placement is contraindicated.<ref name=\":5\" /> Such situations are most commonly due to concerns of contamination in cases where there are infections of the groin, strangulation or perforation of the bowel.<ref name=\":622\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===== Shouldice technique =====\nThe Shouldice technique is the most effective non-mesh repair thus making it one of the most commonly utilized methods.<ref name=\"Scott 2002 CD002197\"/> Numerous studies have been able to validate the conclusion that patients have lower rates of hernia recurrence with the Shouldice technique as compared to other non-mesh repair techniques.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Amato|first=Bruno|last2=Moja|first2=Lorenzo|last3=Panico|first3=Salvatore|last4=Persico|first4=Giovanni|last5=Rispoli|first5=Corrado|last6=Rocco|first6=Nicola|last7=Moschetti|first7=Ivan|date=2012-04-18|title=Shouldice technique versus other open techniques for inguinal hernia repair|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|issue=4|pages=CD001543|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD001543.pub4|issn=1469-493X|pmid=22513902|pmc=6465190}}</ref> However this method frequently experiences longer procedure times and length of hospital stay. Despite being the superior non-mesh technique, the Shouldice method results much higher rates of hernia recurrence in patients when compared to repairs that utilize mesh.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":8\" />[[File:Bassini Operation. The first suture.jpg|thumb|150px|Bassini technique, first suture. 1. Aponeurosis musculi obliq. ext.; 2. Musculus obliquus internus; 3. Musculus transversalis; 4. Fascia transversalis; 5. Peritoneum; 6. Ligamentum inguinale.]]\n\n===== Bassini technique =====\nThe first efficient inguinal hernia repair was described by [[Edoardo Bassini]] in the 1880s.<ref name=\"WhoNamedIt\">{{WhoNamedIt|doctor|3213}}</ref><ref name=\"Bassini1889\">Bassini E, ''Nuovo metodo operativo per la cura dell'ernia inguinale''. Padua, 1889.{{Page needed|date=January 2012}}</ref> In the Bassini technique, the [[conjoint tendon]] (formed by the distal ends of the [[transversus abdominis muscle|transversus abdominis]] and [[Abdominal internal oblique muscle|internal oblique]] muscles) is approximated to the [[inguinal ligament]] and closed.<ref name=\"Gordon1945\">{{cite journal|last1=Gordon|first1=T. L.|year=1945|title=Bassini's Operation for Inguinal Hernia|journal=BMJ|volume=2|issue=4414|pages=181\u20132|doi=10.1136/bmj.2.4414.181|pmc=2059571|pmid=20786215}}</ref>\n\n===== Other open non-mesh techniques =====\nThe Shouldice technique was itself an evolution of prior techniques that had greatly advanced the field of inguinal hernia surgery. Such classic open non-mesh repairs include:<ref name=\":622\"/><ref name=\":5\" />\n* McVay technique\n* Halsted\n* Maloney darn\n* Plication darn\n* [https://doi.org/10.1007%2Fs10029-005-0039-1 Desarda technique]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.desarda.com|title=\"INGUINAL HERNIA REPAIR WITHOUT MESH\"-\"DESARDA REPAIR\"|website=www.desarda.com|access-date=2017-12-10}}</ref> A 1\u20132&nbsp;cm strip of the external oblique aponeurosis is stitched below to the inguinal ligament and above to the muscle arch without disturbing its continuity at either end.[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i00crDtaoQs] This gives immediate protection so no restrictions on activities is required. This is a very simple mesh free and tension free repair based on the physiological principle with very low recurrences and complications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Desarda|first=Mohan P|date=2008-07-01|title=No-mesh inguinal hernia repair with continuous absorbable sutures: A dream or reality? (a study of 229 patients)|journal=Saudi Journal of Gastroenterology|language=en|volume=14|issue=3|pages=122\u2013127|pmc=2702909|pmid=19568520|doi=10.4103/1319-3767.41730}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Szopinski|first=Jacek|last2=Dabrowiecki|first2=Stanislaw|last3=Pierscinski|first3=Stanislaw|last4=Jackowski|first4=Marek|last5=Jaworski|first5=Maciej|last6=Szuflet|first6=Zbigniew|date=2012-05-01|title=Desarda Versus Lichtenstein Technique for Primary Inguinal Hernia Treatment: 3-Year Results of a Randomized Clinical Trial|journal=World Journal of Surgery|language=en|volume=36|issue=5|pages=984\u2013992|doi=10.1007/s00268-012-1508-1|pmid=22392354|pmc=3321139|issn=0364-2313}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gedam|first=B.S.|last2=Bansod|first2=Prasad Y.|last3=Kale|first3=V.B.|last4=Shah|first4=Yunus|last5=Akhtar|first5=Murtaza|title=A comparative study of Desarda's technique with Lichtenstein mesh repair in treatment of inguinal hernia: A prospective cohort study|journal=International Journal of Surgery|volume=39|pages=150\u2013155|doi=10.1016/j.ijsu.2017.01.083|pmid=28131917|year=2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Syed|first=Obaid|date=2017-12-26|title=Desarda's versus Lichtenstein technique of inguinal hernia repair|journal=International Surgery Journal|language=en|volume=5|issue=1|pages=92\u201397|doi=10.18203/2349-2902.isj20175553|issn=2349-2902|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/427e91ed844c23399a41fd8d7626a1310e8bee7d}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Youssef|first=Tamer|last2=El-Alfy|first2=Khaled|last3=Farid|first3=Mohamed|title=Randomized clinical trial of Desarda versus Lichtenstein repair for treatment of primary inguinal hernia|journal=International Journal of Surgery|volume=20|pages=28\u201334|doi=10.1016/j.ijsu.2015.05.055|pmid=26074293|year=2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Emile|first=S. H.|last2=Elfeki|first2=H.|date=2017-09-09|title=Desarda's technique versus Lichtenstein technique for the treatment of primary inguinal hernia: a systematic review and meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials|journal=Hernia|volume=22|issue=3|language=en|pages=385\u2013395|doi=10.1007/s10029-017-1666-z|pmid=28889330|issn=1265-4906}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zulu|first=Halalisani Goodman|last2=Mewa Kinoo|first2=Suman|last3=Singh|first3=Bhugwan|date=July 2016|title=Comparison of Lichtenstein inguinal hernia repair with the tension-free Desarda technique: a clinical audit and review of the literature|journal=Tropical Doctor|volume=46|issue=3|pages=125\u2013129|doi=10.1177/0049475516655070|issn=1758-1133|pmid=27317612|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/4f6f75917def779354efc9da542e4eaae8a69c82}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbas|first=Zaheer|last2=Bhat|first2=Sujeet Kumar|last3=Koul|first3=Monika|last4=Bhat|first4=Rakesh|title=Desarda's No Mesh Repair versus Lichtenstein's Open Mesh Repair of Inguinal Hernia: a comparative study |journal=Journal of Evolution of Medical and Dental Sciences|volume=4|issue=77|pages=13279\u201313285|doi=10.14260/jemds/2015/1910|year=2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.cnki.com.cn/Article_en/CJFDTotal-ZSFD201306013.htm|title=Comparison of the effect of Desarda method and artificial patch in inguinal hernia--\u300aChinese Journal of Hernia and Abdominal Wall Surgery(Electronic Edition)\u300b2013\u5e7406\u671f|website=en.cnki.com.cn|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodr\u00edguez|first=PRl|last2=Herrera|first2=P. P.|last3=Gonzalez|first3=O. L.|last4=Alonso|first4=J. R. C.|last5=Blanco|first5=H. S. R.|date=2013-01-01|title=A Randomized Trial Comparing Lichtenstein Repair and No Mesh Desarda Repair for Inguinal Hernia: A Study of 1382 Patients|url=https://www.ajol.info/index.php/ecajs/article/view/97302|journal=East and Central African Journal of Surgery|language=en|volume=18|issue=2|pages=18\u201325|issn=2073-9990}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Situma|first=S. M.|last2=Kaggwa|first2=S.|last3=Masiira|first3=N. M.|last4=Mutumba|first4=S. K.|date=2009-01-01|title=Comparison of Desarda versus modified Bassini inguinal hernia repair: A randomized controlled trial|url=https://www.ajol.info/index.php/ecajs/article/view/137007|journal=East and Central African Journal of Surgery|volume=14|issue=2|pages=70\u201376|issn=2073-9990}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Neogi|first=Probal|last2=Gupta|first2=Vivek|last3=Tripathi|first3=Neeraj|date=2017-07-24|title=A comparative study of outcomes of Lichtenstein repair and Desarda tissue repair in patients of inguinal hernia|journal=International Surgery Journal|language=en|volume=4|issue=8|pages=2693\u20132699|doi=10.18203/2349-2902.isj20173407|issn=2349-2902}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://medicaljournalofcairouniversity.net/home2/index.php/2014-10-22-23-17-26/vol-83-june-2018/2621-desarda-technique-versus-lichtenstein-mesh-repair-for-the-treatment-of-inguinal-hernia-a-short-term-randomized-controlled-trial|title=Desarda Technique Versus Lichtenstein Mesh Repair for the Treatment of Inguinal Hernia A Short-Term Randomized Controlled Trial|last=User|first=Super|website=medicaljournalofcairouniversity.net|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>\n\n===Laparoscopic repair===\n[[File:Trokar by Groin Hernia repair.jpg|thumb|Port sites for inguinal hernia repair]]\n[[File:Ramus genitalis n genitofemoralis in inguinal canal.jpg|thumb|Intraoperative view by TEP Operation. 1. Genital ramus of genitofemoral nerve. 2. Preperitoneal lipom and spermatic cord.]]\n\nThere are two main methods of laparoscopic repair: ''transabdominal preperitoneal'' (''TAPP'') and ''totally extra-peritoneal'' (''TEP'') repair. When performed by a surgeon experienced in hernia repair, [[laparoscopy|laparoscopic]] repair causes fewer complications than Lichtenstein, particularly less [[inguinodynia|chronic pain]]. However, if the surgeon is experienced in general laparoscopic surgery but not in the specific subject of laparoscopic hernia surgery, laparoscopic repair is not advised as it causes more recurrence risk than Lichtenstein while also presenting risks of serious complications, as organ injury. Indeed, the TAPP approach needs to go through the abdomen. All that said, many surgeons are moving to laparoscopic methodologies as they cause smaller incisions, resulting in less bleeding, less infection, faster recovery, reduced hospitalization, and reduced chronic pain.<ref name=\"Mayo\">http://www.mayoclinic.org/minimally-invasive-surgery{{full citation needed|date=November 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"nice\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/TA83|title=Hernia - laparoscopic surgery (review)|accessdate=2007-03-26|year=2004|work=National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n|+'''Laparoscopic mesh surgery''', as compared to open mesh surgery\n|-\n! Advantages !! Disadvantages\n|-\n|<!--advantages-->\n*Quicker recovery<ref name=\"nice\" /><ref name=\"WashingtonSurgery2008\">{{cite book |author=Trudie A Goers; Washington University School of Medicine Department of Surgery; Klingensmith, Mary E; Li Ern Chen; Sean C Glasgow |title=The Washington manual of surgery|publisher=Wolters Kluwer Health/Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|location=Philadelphia|year=2008 |isbn=978-0-7817-7447-5}}{{Page needed|date=January 2012}}</ref>\n*Less pain during first days<ref name=\"nice\" />\n*Fewer postoperative complications<ref name=\"WashingtonSurgery2008\" />\n:such as infections, bleeding and [[seroma]]s<ref name=\"nice\" />\n*Less risk of chronic pain<ref name=\"nice\" />\n|<!--disadvantages-->\n*Needs surgeon highly experienced\n(>200 operations/year) in inguinal hernia repairs {{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n*Longer operating time<ref name=\"WashingtonSurgery2008\" />\n*Increased recurrence of primary hernias if\nsurgeon not experienced enough<ref name=\"WashingtonSurgery2008\" />\n|}\n\nRecurrence rates are identical when laparoscopy is performed by an experienced surgeon.<ref name=\"nice\" /> When performed by a surgeon less experienced in inguinal hernia lap repair, recurrence is larger than after Lichtenstein.<ref name=\"Neumayer2004\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa040093 |title=Open Mesh versus Laparoscopic Mesh Repair of Inguinal Hernia |year=2004 |last1=Neumayer |first1=Leigh |last2=Giobbie-Hurder |first2=Anita |last3=Jonasson |first3=Olga |last4=Fitzgibbons |first4=Robert |last5=Dunlop |first5=Dorothy |last6=Gibbs |first6=James |last7=Reda |first7=Domenic |last8=Henderson |first8=William |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |volume=350 |issue=18 |pages=1819\u201327 |pmid=15107485 |author9=Veterans Affairs Cooperative Studies Program 456 Investigators |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/51cb22b78cba9d26e6fc58537702677d6f675d89 }}</ref>\n\n== Non-surgical management ==\nStudies have demonstrated that men whose hernias cause little to no symptoms can safely continue to delay surgery until a time that is most convenient for patients and their healthcare team. Research shows that the risk of inguinal hernia complications remains under 1% within the population.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mizrahi|first=Hagar|last2=Parker|first2=Michael C.|date=March 2012|title=Management of asymptomatic inguinal hernia: a systematic review of the evidence|journal=Archives of Surgery|volume=147|issue=3|pages=277\u2013281|doi=10.1001/archsurg.2011.914|issn=1538-3644|pmid=22430913}}</ref><ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/inguinal-hernia/diagnosis-treatment/drc-20351553|title=Inguinal hernia - Diagnosis and treatment - Mayo Clinic|website=www.mayoclinic.org|language=en|access-date=2017-12-05}}</ref><ref name=\":022\"/><ref name=\":622\"/> Watchful waiting requires that patients maintain a close follow-up schedule with providers to monitor the course of their hernia for any changes in symptoms and can be safely offered for up to 2 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.choosingwiselycanada.org/recommendations/general-surgery/|title=The Canadian Association of General Surgeons (CAGS) has developed a list of 6 things physicians and patients should question in general surgery|work=Choosing Wisely Canada|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":222\"/>\n\nPatients who do elect watchful waiting eventually undergo repair within five years as 25% will experience a progression of symptoms such as worsening of pain. Elective repair discussions should be revisited if patient's begin to avoid aspects of their normal routine due to their hernia.<ref name=\":322\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.europeanherniasociety.eu/sites/www.europeanherniasociety.eu/files/medias/PDF/HerniaSurgeGuidelinesStatementsRecomendations.pdf|title=World Guidelines for Hernia Management|website=European Hernia Society|access-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Miserez|first=M.|last2=Peeters|first2=E.|last3=Aufenacker|first3=T.|last4=Bouillot|first4=J. L.|last5=Campanelli|first5=G.|last6=Conze|first6=J.|last7=Fortelny|first7=R.|last8=Heikkinen|first8=T.|last9=Jorgensen|first9=L. N.|date=April 2014|title=Update with level 1 studies of the European Hernia Society guidelines on the treatment of inguinal hernia in adult patients|journal=Hernia|volume=18|issue=2|pages=151\u2013163|doi=10.1007/s10029-014-1236-6|issn=1248-9204|pmid=24647885}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> After 1 year it is estimated that 16% of patients who initially opted for watchful waiting will eventually undergo surgery. Furthermore, 54% and 72% will undergo repair at 5-year and 7.5-year marks respectively.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chung|first=L.|last2=Norrie|first2=J.|last3=O'Dwyer|first3=P. J.|date=April 2011|title=Long-term follow-up of patients with a painless inguinal hernia from a randomized clinical trial|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=98|issue=4|pages=596\u2013599|doi=10.1002/bjs.7355|issn=1365-2168|pmid=21656724|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/b982a8bea7dd81dcdf9b577af9c7102485611839}}</ref><ref name=\":422\"/>\n\nThe use of a [[Truss (medicine)|truss]] is an additional non-surgical option for men. It resembles a jock-strap that utilizes a pad to exert pressure at the site of the hernia in order prevent excursion of the hernia sack. It has little evidence to support its routine use and has not been shown to prevent complications such as incarceration (bowel can no longer slide back into abdomen) or strangulation of bowel (constriction causing loss of blood supply). However some patients do report a soothing of symptoms when utilized.\n\n== Complications and prognosis ==\nInguinal hernia repair complications are unusual, and the procedure as a whole proves to be relatively safe for the majority of patients. Risks inherent in almost all surgical procedures include:<ref name=\":022\"/>\n* bleeding\n* infection\n* [[Seroma|fluid collections]]\n* damage to surrounding structures such as blood vessels, nerves, or the bladder\n* urinary retention requiring a [[urinary catheter|catheter]]\nRisks that are specific to inguinal hernia repairs include such things as:<ref name=\":022\"/><ref name=\":422\"/><ref name=\":622\"/>\n* recurrence of the hernia\n* impairment of sexual activity, such as genital or ejaculatory pain<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aasvang|first=Eske Kvanner|last2=M\u00f8hl|first2=Bo|last3=Bay-Nielsen|first3=Morten|last4=Kehlet|first4=Henrik|date=June 2006|title=Pain related sexual dysfunction after inguinal herniorrhaphy|journal=Pain|volume=122|issue=3|pages=258\u2013263|doi=10.1016/j.pain.2006.01.035|issn=1872-6623|pmid=16545910}}</ref>\n* in males, injury to the [[Vas deferens|tube that conveys sperm]] from the testicle to the penis\n* in males, bruising and swelling of the scrotum\n* chronic regional pain (also known as post-herniorrhaphy inguinodynia, or chronic postoperative inguinal pain)\n\n===Post-herniorraphy pain syndrome===\n[[Post herniorraphy pain syndrome|Post-herniorrhaphy inguinodynia]] is a condition where 10-12% of patients experience severe pain after inguinal hernia repair, due to a complex combination of different [[Pain|forms of pain signals]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kehlet|first=H.|date=February 2008|title=Chronic pain after groin hernia repair|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=95|issue=2|pages=135\u2013136|doi=10.1002/bjs.6111|issn=1365-2168|pmid=18196556}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Callesen|first=T.|last2=Bech|first2=K.|last3=Kehlet|first3=H.|date=December 1999|title=Prospective study of chronic pain after groin hernia repair|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=86|issue=12|pages=1528\u20131531|doi=10.1046/j.1365-2168.1999.01320.x|issn=0007-1323|pmid=10594500}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.europeanherniasociety.eu/sites/www.europeanherniasociety.eu/files/medias/PDF/HerniaSurgeGuidelinesStatementsRecomendations.pdf|title=World Guidelines for Hernia Management|website=European Hernia Society|access-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref> It can occur with any inguinal hernia repair technique, and if unresponsive to pain medications, further surgical intervention is often required.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Starling|first=J. R.|last2=Harms|first2=B. A.|last3=Schroeder|first3=M. E.|last4=Eichman|first4=P. L.|date=October 1987|title=Diagnosis and treatment of genitofemoral and ilioinguinal entrapment neuralgia|journal=Surgery|volume=102|issue=4|pages=581\u2013586|issn=0039-6060|pmid=3660235}}</ref> Removal of the implanted mesh, in combination with [[Neurectomy|bisection of regional nerves]], is commonly performed to address such cases.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aasvang|first=Eske K.|last2=Kehlet|first2=Henrik|date=February 2009|title=The effect of mesh removal and selective neurectomy on persistent postherniotomy pain|journal=Annals of Surgery|volume=249|issue=2|pages=327\u2013334|doi=10.1097/SLA.0b013e31818eec49|issn=1528-1140|pmid=19212190}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zacest|first=Andrew C.|last2=Magill|first2=Stephen T.|last3=Anderson|first3=Valerie C.|last4=Burchiel|first4=Kim J.|date=April 2010|title=Long-term outcome following ilioinguinal neurectomy for chronic pain|journal=Journal of Neurosurgery|volume=112|issue=4|pages=784\u2013789|doi=10.3171/2009.8.JNS09533|issn=1933-0693|pmid=19780646|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/f5659ef97d7a36bafde5f009e5022635954ab1fe}}</ref><ref name=\"Amid 531\u2013536\">{{Cite journal|last=Amid|first=Parviz K.|last2=Chen|first2=David C.|date=October 2011|title=Surgical treatment of chronic groin and testicular pain after laparoscopic and open preperitoneal inguinal hernia repair|journal=Journal of the American College of Surgeons|volume=213|issue=4|pages=531\u2013536|doi=10.1016/j.jamcollsurg.2011.06.424|issn=1879-1190|pmid=21784668}}</ref> There remains ongoing discussion amongst surgeons regarding the utility of planned resections of regional nerves as an attempt to prevent its occurrence.<ref name=\"Amid 531\u2013536\"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Alfieri|first=S.|last2=Amid|first2=P. K.|last3=Campanelli|first3=G.|last4=Izard|first4=G.|last5=Kehlet|first5=H.|last6=Wijsmuller|first6=A. R.|last7=Di Miceli|first7=D.|last8=Doglietto|first8=G. B.|date=June 2011|title=International guidelines for prevention and management of post-operative chronic pain following inguinal hernia surgery|journal=Hernia|volume=15|issue=3|pages=239\u2013249|doi=10.1007/s10029-011-0798-9|issn=1248-9204|pmid=21365287}}</ref>\n\n===Mortality rates===\nMortality rates for non-urgent, elective procedures was demonstrated as 0.1%, and around 3% for procedures performed urgently.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abi-Haidar|first=Youmna|last2=Sanchez|first2=Vivian|last3=Itani|first3=Kamal M. F.|date=September 2011|title=Risk factors and outcomes of acute versus elective groin hernia surgery|journal=Journal of the American College of Surgeons|volume=213|issue=3|pages=363\u2013369|doi=10.1016/j.jamcollsurg.2011.05.008|issn=1879-1190|pmid=21680204}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> Other than urgent repair, risk factors that were also associated with increased mortality included being female, requiring a femoral hernia repair, and older age.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arenal|first=Juan J.|last2=Rodr\u00edguez-Vielba|first2=Paloma|last3=Gallo|first3=Emiliano|last4=Tinoco|first4=Claudia|date=2002|title=Hernias of the abdominal wall in patients over the age of 70 years|journal=The European Journal of Surgery = Acta Chirurgica|volume=168|issue=8\u20139|pages=460\u2013463|doi=10.1080/110241502321116451|issn=1102-4151|pmid=12549685}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Koch|first=A.|last2=Edwards|first2=A.|last3=Haapaniemi|first3=S.|last4=Nordin|first4=P.|last5=Kald|first5=A.|date=December 2005|title=Prospective evaluation of 6895 groin hernia repairs in women|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=92|issue=12|pages=1553\u20131558|doi=10.1002/bjs.5156|issn=0007-1323|pmid=16187268}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dahlstrand|first=Ursula|last2=Wollert|first2=Staffan|last3=Nordin|first3=P\u00e4r|last4=Sandblom|first4=Gabriel|last5=Gunnarsson|first5=Ulf|date=April 2009|title=Emergency femoral hernia repair: a study based on a national register|journal=Annals of Surgery|volume=249|issue=4|pages=672\u2013676|doi=10.1097/SLA.0b013e31819ed943|issn=1528-1140|pmid=19300219}}</ref>\n\n== Follow-up ==\nUpon awakening from anesthesia, patients are monitored for their ability to drink fluids, produce urine, as well as their ability to walk after surgery. Most patients are then able to return home once those conditions are met.<ref name=\":422\"/> It is not uncommon for patients to experience residual soreness for a couple of days after surgery.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hewitt|first=D. Brock|last2=Chojnacki|first2=Karen|date=2017-10-03|title=Laparoscopic Groin Hernia Repair|journal=JAMA|language=en|volume=318|issue=13|pages=1294|doi=10.1001/jama.2017.11620|pmid=28973249|issn=0098-7484}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=Hewitt|first=D. Brock|last2=Chojnacki|first2=Karen|date=2017-08-22|title=Groin Hernia Repair by Open Surgery|journal=JAMA|language=en|volume=318|issue=8|pages=764|doi=10.1001/jama.2017.9868|pmid=28829878|issn=0098-7484}}</ref> Patients are encouraged to make strong efforts in getting up and walking around the day after surgery.<ref name=\":32\" /> Most patients can resume their normal routine of daily living within the week such as driving, showering, light lifting, as well as sexual activity.<ref name=\":022\"/> Long work absences are rarely necessary and length of sick days tend to be dictated by respective employment policies.<ref name=\":32\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn general, it is not recommended to administer antibiotics as prophylaxis after elective inguinal hernia repair. However, the rate of wound infection determines the appropriate use of the antibiotics.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sanchez-Manuel|first1=FJ|last2=Lozano-Garc\u00eda|first2=J|last3=Seco-Gil|first3=JL|title=Antibiotic prophylaxis for hernia repair.|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|date=15 February 2012|issue=2|pages=CD003769|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD003769.pub4|pmid=22336793}}</ref>\n\nPost-op development of any of the following should warrant timely reporting via phone:<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":422\"/>\n* fever greater than 39C/101F\n* progressive swelling of the surgical site\n* severe pain\n* recurring nausea or vomiting\n* worsening redness around incisions\n* drainage of pus from incisions\n* difficulty or lack of producing urine\n* new-onset shortness of breath\n\n== Prevention and screening ==\nMost indirect inguinal hernias in the abdominal wall are not preventable. Direct inguinal hernias may be able to be prevented by maintaining a healthy weight, refraining from smoking, preventing straining during bowel movements, and maintaining proper lifting techniques when heavy lifting.<ref name=\":422\"/><ref name=\":022\"/> There is no evidence that indicates physicians should routinely [[Screening (medicine)|screen]] for asymptomatic inguinal hernias during patient visits.<ref>DynaMed Plus [Internet]. Ipswich (MA): EBSCO Information Services. 1995 - . Record No. 113880, Groin hernia in adults and adolescents; [updated 2017 Nov 27, cited '''Nov 27, 2017''']; [about 28 screens]. Available from <nowiki>http://www.dynamed.com/login.aspx?direct=true&site=DynaMed&id=113880</nowiki>. Registration and login required.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Commons category|Inguinal hernia surgery}}\n\n{{Digestive system surgical procedures}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Inguinal Hernia Repair}}\n[[Category:Inguinal hernias]]\n[[Category:Abdominal surgical procedures]]\n[[Category:Digestive system surgery]]\n\n[[it:Chirurgia dell'ernia inguinale]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical intervention\n| name         = Inguinal hernia surgery\n| synonym      =\n| image        = File:Right Inguinal Hernia.JPG|thumb|\n| caption      = Open surgical repair of a right inguinal hernia\n| alt          = \n| pronounce    = \n| specialty    =gastroenterology\n| synonyms     = \n| ICD10        = \n| ICD9         = \n| ICD9unlinked = \n| CPT          = \n| MeshID       = \n| LOINC        = \n| other_codes  = \n| MedlinePlus  = \n| eMedicine    = \n}}\n'''Inguinal hernia surgery''' is an operation to repair a weakness in the abdominal wall that abnormally allows abdominal contents to slip into a narrow tube called the [[inguinal canal]] in the groin region.\n\nSurgery remains the ultimate treatment for all types of [[hernia]]s as they will not get better on their own, however not all require immediate repair.<ref name=\":022\">{{Cite journal|last=Hewitt|first=D. Brock|date=2017-06-27|title=Groin Hernia|journal=JAMA|language=en|volume=317|issue=24|pages=2560|doi=10.1001/jama.2017.1556|pmid=28655018|issn=0098-7484}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uptodate.com/contents/overview-of-treatment-for-inguinal-and-femoral-hernia-in-adults|title=Overview of treatment for inguinal and femoral hernia in adults|website=www.uptodate.com|access-date=2017-12-14}}</ref> [[Elective surgery]] is offered to most patients taking into account their level of pain, discomfort, degree of disruption in normal activity, as well as their overall level of health.<ref name=\":022\"/> Emergency surgery is typically reserved for patients with life-threatening complications of inguinal hernias such as incarceration and strangulation. Incarceration occurs when [[Omentum majus|intra-abdominal fat]] or small intestine becomes stuck within the canal and cannot slide back into the abdominal cavity either on its own or with [https://emedicine.medscape.com/article/149608-overview?pa=UCBfUUoaBP5LbLkWxNmauKNaMqsTHK4LIi1LCKQSyEuIsCDkyLIA2tdvTZW%2FxVe2TUftft%2BgTNVmHRP6HGZguSchrzF%2F7vlnSF6AEX%2F09M8%3D manual maneuvers]. Left untreated, incarceration may progress to bowel strangulation as a result of restricted blood supply to the trapped segment of small intestine causing that portion to die.<ref name=\":222\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.niddk.nih.gov/health-information/digestive-diseases/inguinal-hernia|title=Inguinal Hernia {{!}} NIDDK|work=National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Successful outcomes of repair are usually measured via rates of hernia recurrence, pain and subsequent quality of life.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.europeanherniasociety.eu/sites/www.europeanherniasociety.eu/files/medias/PDF/HerniaSurgeGuidelinesStatementsRecomendations.pdf|title=World Guidelines for Hernia Management|website=European Hernia Society|access-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSurgical repair of inguinal hernias is one of the most commonly performed operations worldwide and the most commonly performed surgery within the United States. A combined 20 million cases of both inguinal and [[femoral hernia]] repair are performed every year around the world with 800,000 cases in the US as of 2003. The UK reports around 70,000 cases performed every year.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ta83/chapter/6-Implications-for-the-NHS|title=Laparoscopic surgery for inguinal hernia repair {{!}} Guidance and guidelines {{!}} NICE|website=www.nice.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-12-05}}</ref> Groin hernias account for almost 75% of all abdominal wall hernias with the lifetime risk of an inguinal hernia in men and women being 27% and 3% respectively. Men account for nearly 90% of all repairs performed and have a [[Multimodal distribution|bimodal incidence]] of inguinal hernias peaking at 1 year of age and again in those over the age of 40. Although women account for roughly 70% of femoral hernia repairs, indirect inguinal hernias are still the most common subtype of groin hernia in both males and females.<ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://accesssurgery.mhmedical.com/content.aspx?aid=1117751838|title=Schwartz's Principles of Surgery|last=P. Wagner|first=Justin|last2=Brunicardi|first2=F. Charles|last3=Amid|first3=Parviz K.|last4=Chen|first4=David C.|date=2014|publisher=McGraw-Hill Education|editor-last=Brunicardi|editor-first=F. Charles|edition=10|location=New York, NY|editor-last2=Andersen|editor-first2=Dana K.|editor-last3=Billiar|editor-first3=Timothy R.|editor-last4=Dunn|editor-first4=David L.|editor-last5=Hunter|editor-first5=John G.|editor-last6=Matthews|editor-first6=Jeffrey B.|editor-last7=Pollock|editor-first7=Raphael E.|chapter=Inguinal Hernias}}</ref>\n\n== Indications for surgery ==\nSociety guidelines recommend that indications for surgery take into account the severity of symptoms, the type of hernia, previous surgeries, hernia size, bowel incarceration (bowel can no longer return to the abdomen) and the overall general health of the person.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":022\"/><ref name=\":422\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.sages.org/publications/patient-information/patient-information-for-laparoscopic-inguinal-hernia-repair-from-sages/|title=Inguinal Hernia Repair Surgery Information from SAGES|work=SAGES|access-date=2017-12-05|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ta83/chapter/2-Clinical-need-and-practice|title=Laparoscopic surgery for inguinal hernia repair {{!}} Guidance and guidelines {{!}} NICE|website=www.nice.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-12-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Non-urgent repair ===\n[[Elective surgery]] is planned in order to help relieve symptoms, respect the person's preference, and prevent future complications that may require emergency surgery.<ref name=\":5\">DynaMed Plus [Internet]. Ipswich (MA): EBSCO Information Services. 1995 - . Record No. 113880, Groin hernia in adults and adolescents; [updated 2017 Nov 27, cited '''Nov 27, 2017''']; [about 28 screens]. Available from <nowiki>http://www.dynamed.com/login.aspx?direct=true&site=DynaMed&id=113880</nowiki>. Registration and login required.</ref><ref name=\":03\"/>\n\nSurgery is offered to the majority of people who:\n* have symptoms that interfere with their normal level of activity.<ref name=\":422\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n* have hernias that become increasingly difficult to reduce.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":422\" />\n* are female as it is often difficult to classify the subtype of hernia based on an exam alone.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":422\" />\nSymptomatic hernias tend to cause pain or discomfort within the groin region that may increase with exertion and improve with rest. A swollen scrotum within males may coincide with persistent feelings of heaviness or generalized lower abdominal discomfort. The sensation of groin pressure tends to be most prominent at the end of the day as well as after strenuous activities. Changes in sensation may be experienced along the scrotum and inner thigh.<ref name=\":622\">{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://accesssurgery.mhmedical.com/content.aspx?bookid=980&sectionid=59610879#1117751668|title=Schwartz's Principles of Surgery, 10e|last=Wagner|first=Justin|last2=Brunicardi|last3=Amid|last4=Chen|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=2015|isbn=978-0-07179674-3|location=New York, NY|pages=|chapter=Inguinal Hernias}}</ref>\n\n=== Urgent repair ===\nA hernia in which the small intestine has become incarcerated or strangulated constitutes a surgical emergency. Symptoms include:<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":222\"/><ref name=\":622\"/>\n* Fever\n* Nausea and vomiting\n* Extreme pain in the area of the hernia\n* Warm hernia bulge with surrounding skin redness\n* Can no longer pass gas or stool\nSurgical repair within 6 hours of the above symptoms may be able to save the strangulated portion of intestine.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Contraindications to surgery ==\nThe person with the hernia should be given an opportunity to participate in the [[Shared decision-making in medicine|shared decision-making]] with their physicians as almost all procedures carry significant risks. The benefits of inguinal hernia repair can become overshadowed by risks such that elective repair is no longer in a person's best interest. Such cases include:<ref name=\":622\"/><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n* People [[ASA physical status classification system|with unstable medical conditions]]\n* Repair using mesh is withheld if a person has an active infection within the groin or [[Bacteremia|within the blood stream]]\n* Elective repair is delayed in pregnant women until 4 weeks after delivery\nAdditionally, certain medical conditions can prevent people from being candidates for laparoscopic approaches to repair. Examples of such include:<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n* People who are unable to undergo general anesthesia\n* Prior major open abdominal surgery\n* People who have [[ascites]]\n* Previous radiation therapy to the pelvis\n* A complex hernia\n\n== Surgical approaches ==\nTechniques to repair inguinal hernias fall into two broad categories termed \"open\" and \"[[Laparoscopic surgery|laparoscopic]]\". Surgeons tailor their approach by taking into account factors such as their own experience with either techniques, the features of the hernia itself, and the person's anesthetic needs.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":622\"/>\n\nThe cost associated with either approach varies widely across regions. As an example the UK's [[National Health Service|NHS]] spends \u00a356 million a year in repairing inguinal hernias 96% of which were repaired via the open mesh approach while only 4% were done laparoscopically.<ref name=\":7\" /> Updated guidelines published by the International Endohernia Society cast doubt on the comprehensiveness of cost comparison studies due in part to the complexity inherent in calculating costs across institutions.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}} The IES asserts that hospital and societal costs are in fact lower for laparoscopic repairs as compared to open approaches. They recommend the routine use of reusable instruments as well as improving the proficiency of surgeons to help further decrease costs as well as time spent in the OR.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bittner|first=R.|last2=Montgomery|first2=M. A.|last3=Arregui|first3=E.|last4=Bansal|first4=V.|last5=Bingener|first5=J.|last6=Bisgaard|first6=T.|last7=Buhck|first7=H.|last8=Dudai|first8=M.|last9=Ferzli|first9=G. S.|date=2015|title=Update of guidelines on laparoscopic (TAPP) and endoscopic (TEP) treatment of inguinal hernia (International Endohernia Society)|journal=Surgical Endoscopy|volume=29|issue=2|pages=289\u2013321|doi=10.1007/s00464-014-3917-8|issn=0930-2794|pmc=4293469|pmid=25398194}}</ref>\n\n=== Open hernia repair ===\nAll techniques involve an approximate 10-cm incision in the groin. Once exposed, the hernia sac is returned to the abdominal cavity  or excised and the abdominal wall is very often reinforced with [[Surgical mesh|mesh]].<ref name=\":222\"/> There are many techniques that do not utilize mesh and have their own situations where they are preferable.<ref name=\":22\"/><ref name=\":422\"/>\n\nOpen repairs are classified via whether prosthetic mesh is utilized or whether the patient's own tissue is used to repair the weakness. Prosthetic repairs enable surgeons to repair a hernia without causing undue tension in the surrounding tissues while reinforcing the abdominal wall. Repairs with undue tension have been shown to increase the likelihood that the hernia will recur. Repairs not using prosthetic mesh are preferable options in patients with an above-average risk of infection such as cases where the bowel has become strangulated (blood supply lost due to constriction).<ref name=\":622\"/>\n\nOne large benefit of this approach lies in its ability to tailor anesthesia to a person's needs. People can be administered [[local anesthesia]], a [[Spinal anaesthesia|spinal block]], as well as [[General anaesthesia|general anesthesia]].<ref name=\":5\" /> Local anesthesia has been shown to cause less pain after surgery, shorten operating times, shorten recovery times as well as decrease the need to return to the hospital. However, people who undergo general anesthesia tend to be able to go home faster and experience fewer complications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nordin|first=P\u00e4r|last2=Zetterstr\u00f6m|first2=Henrik|last3=Gunnarsson|first3=Ulf|last4=Nilsson|first4=Erik|date=2003-09-13|title=Local, regional, or general anaesthesia in groin hernia repair: multicentre randomised trial|journal=Lancet|volume=362|issue=9387|pages=853\u2013858|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(03)14339-5|issn=1474-547X|pmid=13678971}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=van Veen|first=Ruben N.|last2=Mahabier|first2=Chander|last3=Dawson|first3=Imro|last4=Hop|first4=Wim C.|last5=Kok|first5=Niels F. M.|last6=Lange|first6=Johan F.|last7=Jeekel|first7=Johannus|date=March 2008|title=Spinal or local anesthesia in lichtenstein hernia repair: a randomized controlled trial|journal=Annals of Surgery|volume=247|issue=3|pages=428\u2013433|doi=10.1097/SLA.0b013e318165b0ff|issn=0003-4932|pmid=18376185}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> The European Hernia Society recommends the use of local anesthesia particularly for people with ongoing medical conditions.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== Open mesh repairs ====\n[[File:Hernia mesh 1.jpg|thumb|Polypropylene mesh used for inguinal hernia surgery]]\n[[File:Inguinal Hernia Patch.png|thumb|Inguinal Hernia Patch. Animation in the reference.]]\n\nRepairs that utilize mesh are usually the first recommendation for the vast majority of patients including those that undergo laparoscopic repair.<ref name=\":3\" /> Procedures that employ mesh are the most commonly performed as they have been able to demonstrate greater results as compared to non-mesh repairs.<ref name=\":622\"/> Approaches utilizing mesh have been able to demonstrate faster return to usual activity, lower rates of persistent pain, shorter hospital stays, and a lower likelihood that the hernia will recur.<ref name=\"Scott 2002 CD002197\">{{Cite journal|last=Scott|first=N. W.|last2=McCormack|first2=K.|last3=Graham|first3=P.|last4=Go|first4=P. M.|last5=Ross|first5=S. J.|last6=Grant|first6=A. M.|date=2002|title=Open mesh versus non-mesh for repair of femoral and inguinal hernia|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|issue=4|pages=CD002197|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD002197|issn=1469-493X|pmid=12519568|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/7dfaf6207dca8eb11e07e53f702a61104e60fbeb}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rosenberg|first=Jacob|last2=Bisgaard|first2=Thue|last3=Kehlet|first3=Henrik|last4=Wara|first4=P\u00e5l|last5=Asmussen|first5=Torsten|last6=Juul|first6=Poul|last7=Strand|first7=Lasse|last8=Andersen|first8=Finn Heidmann|last9=Bay-Nielsen|first9=Morten|date=February 2011|title=Danish Hernia Database recommendations for the management of inguinal and femoral hernia in adults|journal=Danish Medical Bulletin|volume=58|issue=2|pages=C4243|issn=1603-9629|pmid=21299930}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bay-Nielsen|first=M.|last2=Kehlet|first2=H.|last3=Strand|first3=L.|last4=Malmstr\u00f8m|first4=J.|last5=Andersen|first5=F. H.|last6=Wara|first6=P.|last7=Juul|first7=P.|last8=Callesen|first8=T.|last9=Danish Hernia Database Collaboration|date=2001-10-06|title=Quality assessment of 26,304 herniorrhaphies in Denmark: a prospective nationwide study|journal=Lancet|volume=358|issue=9288|pages=1124\u20131128|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(01)06251-1|issn=0140-6736|pmid=11597665}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Matthews|first=Richard D.|last2=Anthony|first2=Thomas|last3=Kim|first3=Lawrence T.|last4=Wang|first4=Jia|last5=Fitzgibbons|first5=Robert J.|last6=Giobbie-Hurder|first6=Anita|last7=Reda|first7=Domenic J.|last8=Itani|first8=Kamal M. F.|last9=Neumayer|first9=Leigh A.|date=November 2007|title=Factors associated with postoperative complications and hernia recurrence for patients undergoing inguinal hernia repair: a report from the VA Cooperative Hernia Study Group|journal=American Journal of Surgery|volume=194|issue=5|pages=611\u2013617|doi=10.1016/j.amjsurg.2007.07.018|issn=1879-1883|pmid=17936422}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=EU Hernia Trialists Collaboration|date=March 2002|title=Repair of groin hernia with synthetic mesh: meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials|journal=Annals of Surgery|volume=235|issue=3|pages=322\u2013332|issn=0003-4932|pmc=1422456|pmid=11882753|doi=10.1097/00000658-200203000-00003}}</ref>\n\nOptions for mesh include either [[Surgical mesh|synthetic]] or [[Biomesh|biologic]]. Synthetic mesh provides the option of using \"heavyweight\" as well as \"lightweight\" variations according to the diameter and number of mesh fibers.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Earle|first=David B.|last2=Mark|first2=Lisa A.|date=February 2008|title=Prosthetic material in inguinal hernia repair: how do I choose?|journal=The Surgical Clinics of North America|volume=88|issue=1|pages=179\u2013201, x|doi=10.1016/j.suc.2007.11.002|issn=0039-6109|pmid=18267169}}</ref> Lightweight mesh has been shown to have fewer complications related to the mesh itself than its heavyweight counterparts.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bittner|first=R.|last2=Arregui|first2=M. E.|last3=Bisgaard|first3=T.|last4=Dudai|first4=M.|last5=Ferzli|first5=G. S.|last6=Fitzgibbons|first6=R. J.|last7=Fortelny|first7=R. H.|last8=Klinge|first8=U.|last9=Kockerling|first9=F.|date=September 2011|title=Guidelines for laparoscopic (TAPP) and endoscopic (TEP) treatment of inguinal hernia [International Endohernia Society (IEHS)]|journal=Surgical Endoscopy|volume=25|issue=9|pages=2773\u20132843|doi=10.1007/s00464-011-1799-6|issn=1432-2218|pmc=3160575|pmid=21751060}}</ref> It was additionally correlated with lower rates of chronic pain while sharing the same rates of hernia recurrence as compared to heavyweight options.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sajid|first=Muhammad S.|last2=Kalra|first2=Lorain|last3=Parampalli|first3=Umesh|last4=Sains|first4=Parv S.|last5=Baig|first5=Mirza K.|date=June 2013|title=A systematic review and meta-analysis evaluating the effectiveness of lightweight mesh against heavyweight mesh in influencing the incidence of chronic groin pain following laparoscopic inguinal hernia repair|journal=American Journal of Surgery|volume=205|issue=6|pages=726\u2013736|doi=10.1016/j.amjsurg.2012.07.046|issn=1879-1883|pmid=23561639}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sajid|first=M. S.|last2=Leaver|first2=C.|last3=Baig|first3=M. K.|last4=Sains|first4=P.|date=January 2012|title=Systematic review and meta-analysis of the use of lightweight versus heavyweight mesh in open inguinal hernia repair|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=99|issue=1|pages=29\u201337|doi=10.1002/bjs.7718|issn=1365-2168|pmid=22038579}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bittner|first=R.|last2=Montgomery|first2=M. A.|last3=Arregui|first3=E.|last4=Bansal|first4=V.|last5=Bingener|first5=J.|last6=Bisgaard|first6=T.|last7=Buhck|first7=H.|last8=Dudai|first8=M.|last9=Ferzli|first9=G. S.|date=2015-02-01|title=Update of guidelines on laparoscopic (TAPP) and endoscopic (TEP) treatment of inguinal hernia (International Endohernia Society)|journal=Surgical Endoscopy|language=en|volume=29|issue=2|pages=289\u2013321|doi=10.1007/s00464-014-3917-8|pmid=25398194|pmc=4293469|issn=0930-2794}}</ref> This has led to the adoption of lightweight mesh for minimizing the chance of chronic pain after surgery.<ref name=\":622\"/> Biologic mesh is indicated in cases where the risk of infection is a major concern such as cases in which the bowel has become strangulated. They tend to have lower [[Ultimate tensile strength|tensile strength]] than their synthetic counterparts lending them to higher rates of mesh rupture.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Smart|first=Neil J.|last2=Bloor|first2=Stephen|date=September 2012|title=Durability of biologic implants for use in hernia repair: a review|journal=Surgical Innovation|volume=19|issue=3|pages=221\u2013229|doi=10.1177/1553350611429027|issn=1553-3514|pmid=22143748}}</ref>\n\nBiomeshes are increasingly popular since their first use in 1999<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Edelman|first1=DS|last2=Hodde|first2=JP|year=2006|title=Bioactive prosthetic material for treatment of hernias|journal=Surgical Technology International|volume=15|pages=104\u20138|pmid=17029169}}</ref> and their subsequent introduction on the market in 2003. Some meshes have a price comparable to the high end of synthetic meshes, the cheapest ($500) being Surgisis-Biodesign, manufactured by [[Cook Group]], made from the [[extra cellular matrix]] of pig [[small intestinal submucosa]].<ref>Inguinal Hernia Repair with Biodesign\u00ae (Surgisis\u00ae) -- David Edelman, MD [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zieBX96y0rQ]{{Unreliable medical source|date=January 2012}}</ref> Currently, there exists one synthetic totally absorbable mesh, Tigr Matrix, manufactured by [[Novus Scientific]], on the US market (510(k) [[Food and Drug Administration]] clearance)<ref>http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/cdrh_docs/pdf9/K092224.pdf{{full citation needed|date=November 2012}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> since 2010 and on the EU market since 2011. It only has one 3-year [[Clinical trial#Pre-clinical studies|pre-clinical evidence]] on [[sheep]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hjort|first1=H.|last2=Mathisen|first2=T.|last3=Alves|first3=A.|last4=Clermont|first4=G.|last5=Boutrand|first5=J. P.|year=2011|title=Three-year results from a preclinical implantation study of a long-term resorbable surgical mesh with time-dependent mechanical characteristics|journal=Hernia|volume=16|issue=2|pages=191\u20137|doi=10.1007/s10029-011-0885-y|pmc=3895198|pmid=21972049}}</ref>\n\nMeshes made of [[mosquito net]] cloth, in [[copolymer]] of [[polyethylene]] and [[polypropylene]] have been used for low-income patients in rural [[India]] and [[Ghana]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Clarke|first1=M. G.|last2=Oppong|first2=C.|last3=Simmermacher|first3=R.|last4=Park|first4=K.|last5=Kurzer|first5=M.|last6=Vanotoo|first6=L.|last7=Kingsnorth|first7=A. N.|year=2008|title=The use of sterilised polyester mosquito net mesh for inguinal hernia repair in Ghana|journal=Hernia|volume=13|issue=2|pages=155\u20139|doi=10.1007/s10029-008-0460-3|pmid=19089526}}</ref> Each piece costs $0.01, 3700 times cheaper than an equivalent commercial mesh.<ref name=\"Tongaonkar03\">{{cite journal|last1=Tongaonkar|first1=Ravindranath R.|last2=Reddy|first2=Brahma V.|last3=Mehta|first3=Virendra K.|last4=Singh|first4=Ningthoujam Somorjit|last5=Shivade|first5=Sanjay|year=2003|title=Preliminary Multicentric Trial of Cheap Indigenous Mosquito-Net Cloth for Tension-free Hernia Repair|url=http://www.bioline.org.br/request?is03018|journal=Indian Journal of Surgery|volume=65|issue=1|pages=89\u201395}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wilhelm|first1=T.J.|last2=Freudenberg|first2=S.|last3=Jonas|first3=E.|last4=Grobholz|first4=R.|last5=Post|first5=S.|last6=Kyamanywa|first6=P.|year=2007|title=Sterilized Mosquito Net versus Commercial Mesh for Hernia Repair|journal=European Surgical Research|volume=39|issue=5|pages=312\u20137|doi=10.1159/000104402|pmid=17595545}}</ref> They give results identical to commercial meshes in terms of infection and recurrence rate at 5 years.<ref name=\"Tongaonkar03\" />\n\n===== Lichtenstein technique =====\nThe Lichtenstein tension-free repair has persisted as one of the most commonly performed procedures in the world. The European Hernia Society recommends that in cases where an open approach is indicated, the Lichtenstein technique be utilized as the preferred method.<ref name=\":3\" /> Recent studies have indicated that mesh attachment with the use of [[Butyl cyanoacrylate|adhesive glue]] is faster and less likely to cause post-op pain as compared to attachment via suture material.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sun|first=Ping|last2=Cheng|first2=Xiang|last3=Deng|first3=Shichang|last4=Hu|first4=Qinggang|last5=Sun|first5=Yi|last6=Zheng|first6=Qichang|date=7 Feb 2017|title=Mesh fixation with glue versus suture for chronic pain and recurrence in Lichtenstein inguinal hernioplasty|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=2|pages=CD010814|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD010814.pub2|issn=1469-493X|pmid=28170080|pmc=6464532}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=de Goede|first=B.|last2=Klitsie|first2=P. J.|last3=van Kempen|first3=B. J. H.|last4=Timmermans|first4=L.|last5=Jeekel|first5=J.|last6=Kazemier|first6=G.|last7=Lange|first7=J. F.|date=May 2013|title=Meta-analysis of glue versus sutured mesh fixation for Lichtenstein inguinal hernia repair|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=100|issue=6|pages=735\u2013742|doi=10.1002/bjs.9072|issn=1365-2168|pmid=23436683}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shen|first=Ying-mo|last2=Sun|first2=Wen-bing|last3=Chen|first3=Jie|last4=Liu|first4=Su-jun|last5=Wang|first5=Ming-gang|date=April 2012|title=NBCA medical adhesive (n-butyl-2-cyanoacrylate) versus suture for patch fixation in Lichtenstein inguinal herniorrhaphy: a randomized controlled trial|journal=Surgery|volume=151|issue=4|pages=550\u2013555|doi=10.1016/j.surg.2011.09.031|issn=1532-7361|pmid=22088820}}</ref>\n\n===== Plug and patch technique =====\nThe plug and patch tension-free technique has fallen out of favor due to higher rates of mesh shift along with its tendency to irritate surrounding tissue. This has led to the European Hernia Society recommending that the technique not be used in most cases.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n===== Other open mesh repair techniques =====\nA variety of other tension-free techniques have been developed and include:<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":622\"/>\n* Prolene mesh system (PHS)\n* Kugel (preperitoneal repair)<ref>[https://jomi.com/article/8/minimally-invasive-open-inguinal-hernia-repair] Reinhorn M. Minimally invasive open preperitoneal inguinal hernia repair. J Med Ins. 2014;2014(8). doi:https://doi.org/10.24296/jomi/8</ref>\n* Stoppa\n* Trabucco (Hertra mesh)\n* Wantz\n* Rutkow/Robbins\n* mAPP\n\n==== Open non-mesh repairs ====\nTechniques in which mesh is not used are referred to as tissue repair technique, suture technique, and tension technique. All involve bringing together the tissue with sutures and are a viable alternative when mesh placement is contraindicated.<ref name=\":5\" /> Such situations are most commonly due to concerns of contamination in cases where there are infections of the groin, strangulation or perforation of the bowel.<ref name=\":622\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===== Shouldice technique =====\nThe Shouldice technique is the most effective non-mesh repair thus making it one of the most commonly utilized methods.<ref name=\"Scott 2002 CD002197\"/> Numerous studies have been able to validate the conclusion that patients have lower rates of hernia recurrence with the Shouldice technique as compared to other non-mesh repair techniques.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Amato|first=Bruno|last2=Moja|first2=Lorenzo|last3=Panico|first3=Salvatore|last4=Persico|first4=Giovanni|last5=Rispoli|first5=Corrado|last6=Rocco|first6=Nicola|last7=Moschetti|first7=Ivan|date=2012-04-18|title=Shouldice technique versus other open techniques for inguinal hernia repair|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|issue=4|pages=CD001543|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD001543.pub4|issn=1469-493X|pmid=22513902|pmc=6465190}}</ref> However this method frequently experiences longer procedure times and length of hospital stay. Despite being the superior non-mesh technique, the Shouldice method results much higher rates of hernia recurrence in patients when compared to repairs that utilize mesh.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":8\" />[[File:Bassini Operation. The first suture.jpg|thumb|150px|Bassini technique, first suture. 1. Aponeurosis musculi obliq. ext.; 2. Musculus obliquus internus; 3. Musculus transversalis; 4. Fascia transversalis; 5. Peritoneum; 6. Ligamentum inguinale.]]\n\n===== Bassini technique =====\nThe first efficient inguinal hernia repair was described by [[Edoardo Bassini]] in the 1880s.<ref name=\"WhoNamedIt\">{{WhoNamedIt|doctor|3213}}</ref><ref name=\"Bassini1889\">Bassini E, ''Nuovo metodo operativo per la cura dell'ernia inguinale''. Padua, 1889.{{Page needed|date=January 2012}}</ref> In the Bassini technique, the [[conjoint tendon]] (formed by the distal ends of the [[transversus abdominis muscle|transversus abdominis]] and [[Abdominal internal oblique muscle|internal oblique]] muscles) is approximated to the [[inguinal ligament]] and closed.<ref name=\"Gordon1945\">{{cite journal|last1=Gordon|first1=T. L.|year=1945|title=Bassini's Operation for Inguinal Hernia|journal=BMJ|volume=2|issue=4414|pages=181\u20132|doi=10.1136/bmj.2.4414.181|pmc=2059571|pmid=20786215}}</ref>\n\n===== Other open non-mesh techniques =====\nThe Shouldice technique was itself an evolution of prior techniques that had greatly advanced the field of inguinal hernia surgery. Such classic open non-mesh repairs include:<ref name=\":622\"/><ref name=\":5\" />\n* McVay technique\n* Halsted\n* Maloney darn\n* Plication darn\n* [https://doi.org/10.1007%2Fs10029-005-0039-1 Desarda technique]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.desarda.com|title=\"INGUINAL HERNIA REPAIR WITHOUT MESH\"-\"DESARDA REPAIR\"|website=www.desarda.com|access-date=2017-12-10}}</ref> A 1\u20132&nbsp;cm strip of the external oblique aponeurosis is stitched below to the inguinal ligament and above to the muscle arch without disturbing its continuity at either end.[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i00crDtaoQs] This gives immediate protection so no restrictions on activities is required. This is a very simple mesh free and tension free repair based on the physiological principle with very low recurrences and complications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Desarda|first=Mohan P|date=2008-07-01|title=No-mesh inguinal hernia repair with continuous absorbable sutures: A dream or reality? (a study of 229 patients)|journal=Saudi Journal of Gastroenterology|language=en|volume=14|issue=3|pages=122\u2013127|pmc=2702909|pmid=19568520|doi=10.4103/1319-3767.41730}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Szopinski|first=Jacek|last2=Dabrowiecki|first2=Stanislaw|last3=Pierscinski|first3=Stanislaw|last4=Jackowski|first4=Marek|last5=Jaworski|first5=Maciej|last6=Szuflet|first6=Zbigniew|date=2012-05-01|title=Desarda Versus Lichtenstein Technique for Primary Inguinal Hernia Treatment: 3-Year Results of a Randomized Clinical Trial|journal=World Journal of Surgery|language=en|volume=36|issue=5|pages=984\u2013992|doi=10.1007/s00268-012-1508-1|pmid=22392354|pmc=3321139|issn=0364-2313}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gedam|first=B.S.|last2=Bansod|first2=Prasad Y.|last3=Kale|first3=V.B.|last4=Shah|first4=Yunus|last5=Akhtar|first5=Murtaza|title=A comparative study of Desarda's technique with Lichtenstein mesh repair in treatment of inguinal hernia: A prospective cohort study|journal=International Journal of Surgery|volume=39|pages=150\u2013155|doi=10.1016/j.ijsu.2017.01.083|pmid=28131917|year=2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Syed|first=Obaid|date=2017-12-26|title=Desarda's versus Lichtenstein technique of inguinal hernia repair|journal=International Surgery Journal|language=en|volume=5|issue=1|pages=92\u201397|doi=10.18203/2349-2902.isj20175553|issn=2349-2902|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/427e91ed844c23399a41fd8d7626a1310e8bee7d}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Youssef|first=Tamer|last2=El-Alfy|first2=Khaled|last3=Farid|first3=Mohamed|title=Randomized clinical trial of Desarda versus Lichtenstein repair for treatment of primary inguinal hernia|journal=International Journal of Surgery|volume=20|pages=28\u201334|doi=10.1016/j.ijsu.2015.05.055|pmid=26074293|year=2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Emile|first=S. H.|last2=Elfeki|first2=H.|date=2017-09-09|title=Desarda's technique versus Lichtenstein technique for the treatment of primary inguinal hernia: a systematic review and meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials|journal=Hernia|volume=22|issue=3|language=en|pages=385\u2013395|doi=10.1007/s10029-017-1666-z|pmid=28889330|issn=1265-4906}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zulu|first=Halalisani Goodman|last2=Mewa Kinoo|first2=Suman|last3=Singh|first3=Bhugwan|date=July 2016|title=Comparison of Lichtenstein inguinal hernia repair with the tension-free Desarda technique: a clinical audit and review of the literature|journal=Tropical Doctor|volume=46|issue=3|pages=125\u2013129|doi=10.1177/0049475516655070|issn=1758-1133|pmid=27317612|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/4f6f75917def779354efc9da542e4eaae8a69c82}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abbas|first=Zaheer|last2=Bhat|first2=Sujeet Kumar|last3=Koul|first3=Monika|last4=Bhat|first4=Rakesh|title=Desarda's No Mesh Repair versus Lichtenstein's Open Mesh Repair of Inguinal Hernia: a comparative study |journal=Journal of Evolution of Medical and Dental Sciences|volume=4|issue=77|pages=13279\u201313285|doi=10.14260/jemds/2015/1910|year=2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.cnki.com.cn/Article_en/CJFDTotal-ZSFD201306013.htm|title=Comparison of the effect of Desarda method and artificial patch in inguinal hernia--\u300aChinese Journal of Hernia and Abdominal Wall Surgery(Electronic Edition)\u300b2013\u5e7406\u671f|website=en.cnki.com.cn|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rodr\u00edguez|first=PRl|last2=Herrera|first2=P. P.|last3=Gonzalez|first3=O. L.|last4=Alonso|first4=J. R. C.|last5=Blanco|first5=H. S. R.|date=2013-01-01|title=A Randomized Trial Comparing Lichtenstein Repair and No Mesh Desarda Repair for Inguinal Hernia: A Study of 1382 Patients|url=https://www.ajol.info/index.php/ecajs/article/view/97302|journal=East and Central African Journal of Surgery|language=en|volume=18|issue=2|pages=18\u201325|issn=2073-9990}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Situma|first=S. M.|last2=Kaggwa|first2=S.|last3=Masiira|first3=N. M.|last4=Mutumba|first4=S. K.|date=2009-01-01|title=Comparison of Desarda versus modified Bassini inguinal hernia repair: A randomized controlled trial|url=https://www.ajol.info/index.php/ecajs/article/view/137007|journal=East and Central African Journal of Surgery|volume=14|issue=2|pages=70\u201376|issn=2073-9990}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Neogi|first=Probal|last2=Gupta|first2=Vivek|last3=Tripathi|first3=Neeraj|date=2017-07-24|title=A comparative study of outcomes of Lichtenstein repair and Desarda tissue repair in patients of inguinal hernia|journal=International Surgery Journal|language=en|volume=4|issue=8|pages=2693\u20132699|doi=10.18203/2349-2902.isj20173407|issn=2349-2902}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://medicaljournalofcairouniversity.net/home2/index.php/2014-10-22-23-17-26/vol-83-june-2018/2621-desarda-technique-versus-lichtenstein-mesh-repair-for-the-treatment-of-inguinal-hernia-a-short-term-randomized-controlled-trial|title=Desarda Technique Versus Lichtenstein Mesh Repair for the Treatment of Inguinal Hernia A Short-Term Randomized Controlled Trial|last=User|first=Super|website=medicaljournalofcairouniversity.net|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>\n\n===Laparoscopic repair===\n[[File:Trokar by Groin Hernia repair.jpg|thumb|Port sites for inguinal hernia repair]]\n[[File:Ramus genitalis n genitofemoralis in inguinal canal.jpg|thumb|Intraoperative view by TEP Operation. 1. Genital ramus of genitofemoral nerve. 2. Preperitoneal lipom and spermatic cord.]]\n\nThere are two main methods of laparoscopic repair: ''transabdominal preperitoneal'' (''TAPP'') and ''totally extra-peritoneal'' (''TEP'') repair. When performed by a surgeon experienced in hernia repair, [[laparoscopy|laparoscopic]] repair causes fewer complications than Lichtenstein, particularly less [[inguinodynia|chronic pain]]. However, if the surgeon is experienced in general laparoscopic surgery but not in the specific subject of laparoscopic hernia surgery, laparoscopic repair is not advised as it causes more recurrence risk than Lichtenstein while also presenting risks of serious complications, as organ injury. Indeed, the TAPP approach needs to go through the abdomen. All that said, many surgeons are moving to laparoscopic methodologies as they cause smaller incisions, resulting in less bleeding, less infection, faster recovery, reduced hospitalization, and reduced chronic pain.<ref name=\"Mayo\">http://www.mayoclinic.org/minimally-invasive-surgery{{full citation needed|date=November 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"nice\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/TA83|title=Hernia - laparoscopic surgery (review)|accessdate=2007-03-26|year=2004|work=National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n|+'''Laparoscopic mesh surgery''', as compared to open mesh surgery\n|-\n! Advantages !! Disadvantages\n|-\n|<!--advantages-->\n*Quicker recovery<ref name=\"nice\" /><ref name=\"WashingtonSurgery2008\">{{cite book |author=Trudie A Goers; Washington University School of Medicine Department of Surgery; Klingensmith, Mary E; Li Ern Chen; Sean C Glasgow |title=The Washington manual of surgery|publisher=Wolters Kluwer Health/Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|location=Philadelphia|year=2008 |isbn=978-0-7817-7447-5}}{{Page needed|date=January 2012}}</ref>\n*Less pain during first days<ref name=\"nice\" />\n*Fewer postoperative complications<ref name=\"WashingtonSurgery2008\" />\n:such as infections, bleeding and [[seroma]]s<ref name=\"nice\" />\n*Less risk of chronic pain<ref name=\"nice\" />\n|<!--disadvantages-->\n*Needs surgeon highly experienced\n(>200 operations/year) in inguinal hernia repairs {{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n*Longer operating time<ref name=\"WashingtonSurgery2008\" />\n*Increased recurrence of primary hernias if\nsurgeon not experienced enough<ref name=\"WashingtonSurgery2008\" />\n|}\n\nRecurrence rates are identical when laparoscopy is performed by an experienced surgeon.<ref name=\"nice\" /> When performed by a surgeon less experienced in inguinal hernia lap repair, recurrence is larger than after Lichtenstein.<ref name=\"Neumayer2004\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa040093 |title=Open Mesh versus Laparoscopic Mesh Repair of Inguinal Hernia |year=2004 |last1=Neumayer |first1=Leigh |last2=Giobbie-Hurder |first2=Anita |last3=Jonasson |first3=Olga |last4=Fitzgibbons |first4=Robert |last5=Dunlop |first5=Dorothy |last6=Gibbs |first6=James |last7=Reda |first7=Domenic |last8=Henderson |first8=William |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |volume=350 |issue=18 |pages=1819\u201327 |pmid=15107485 |author9=Veterans Affairs Cooperative Studies Program 456 Investigators |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/51cb22b78cba9d26e6fc58537702677d6f675d89 }}</ref>\n\n== Non-surgical management ==\nStudies have demonstrated that men whose hernias cause little to no symptoms can safely continue to delay surgery until a time that is most convenient for patients and their healthcare team. Research shows that the risk of inguinal hernia complications remains under 1% within the population.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mizrahi|first=Hagar|last2=Parker|first2=Michael C.|date=March 2012|title=Management of asymptomatic inguinal hernia: a systematic review of the evidence|journal=Archives of Surgery|volume=147|issue=3|pages=277\u2013281|doi=10.1001/archsurg.2011.914|issn=1538-3644|pmid=22430913}}</ref><ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/inguinal-hernia/diagnosis-treatment/drc-20351553|title=Inguinal hernia - Diagnosis and treatment - Mayo Clinic|website=www.mayoclinic.org|language=en|access-date=2017-12-05}}</ref><ref name=\":022\"/><ref name=\":622\"/> Watchful waiting requires that patients maintain a close follow-up schedule with providers to monitor the course of their hernia for any changes in symptoms and can be safely offered for up to 2 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.choosingwiselycanada.org/recommendations/general-surgery/|title=The Canadian Association of General Surgeons (CAGS) has developed a list of 6 things physicians and patients should question in general surgery|work=Choosing Wisely Canada|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":222\"/>\n\nPatients who do elect watchful waiting eventually undergo repair within five years as 25% will experience a progression of symptoms such as worsening of pain. Elective repair discussions should be revisited if patient's begin to avoid aspects of their normal routine due to their hernia.<ref name=\":322\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.europeanherniasociety.eu/sites/www.europeanherniasociety.eu/files/medias/PDF/HerniaSurgeGuidelinesStatementsRecomendations.pdf|title=World Guidelines for Hernia Management|website=European Hernia Society|access-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Miserez|first=M.|last2=Peeters|first2=E.|last3=Aufenacker|first3=T.|last4=Bouillot|first4=J. L.|last5=Campanelli|first5=G.|last6=Conze|first6=J.|last7=Fortelny|first7=R.|last8=Heikkinen|first8=T.|last9=Jorgensen|first9=L. N.|date=April 2014|title=Update with level 1 studies of the European Hernia Society guidelines on the treatment of inguinal hernia in adult patients|journal=Hernia|volume=18|issue=2|pages=151\u2013163|doi=10.1007/s10029-014-1236-6|issn=1248-9204|pmid=24647885}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> After 1 year it is estimated that 16% of patients who initially opted for watchful waiting will eventually undergo surgery. Furthermore, 54% and 72% will undergo repair at 5-year and 7.5-year marks respectively.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chung|first=L.|last2=Norrie|first2=J.|last3=O'Dwyer|first3=P. J.|date=April 2011|title=Long-term follow-up of patients with a painless inguinal hernia from a randomized clinical trial|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=98|issue=4|pages=596\u2013599|doi=10.1002/bjs.7355|issn=1365-2168|pmid=21656724|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/b982a8bea7dd81dcdf9b577af9c7102485611839}}</ref><ref name=\":422\"/>\n\nThe use of a [[Truss (medicine)|truss]] is an additional non-surgical option for men. It resembles a jock-strap that utilizes a pad to exert pressure at the site of the hernia in order prevent excursion of the hernia sack. It has little evidence to support its routine use and has not been shown to prevent complications such as incarceration (bowel can no longer slide back into abdomen) or strangulation of bowel (constriction causing loss of blood supply). However some patients do report a soothing of symptoms when utilized.\n\n== Complications and prognosis ==\nInguinal hernia repair complications are unusual, and the procedure as a whole proves to be relatively safe for the majority of patients. Risks inherent in almost all surgical procedures include:<ref name=\":022\"/>\n* bleeding\n* infection\n* [[Seroma|fluid collections]]\n* damage to surrounding structures such as blood vessels, nerves, or the bladder\n* urinary retention requiring a [[urinary catheter|catheter]]\nRisks that are specific to inguinal hernia repairs include such things as:<ref name=\":022\"/><ref name=\":422\"/><ref name=\":622\"/>\n* recurrence of the hernia\n* impairment of sexual activity, such as genital or ejaculatory pain<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aasvang|first=Eske Kvanner|last2=M\u00f8hl|first2=Bo|last3=Bay-Nielsen|first3=Morten|last4=Kehlet|first4=Henrik|date=June 2006|title=Pain related sexual dysfunction after inguinal herniorrhaphy|journal=Pain|volume=122|issue=3|pages=258\u2013263|doi=10.1016/j.pain.2006.01.035|issn=1872-6623|pmid=16545910}}</ref>\n* in males, injury to the [[Vas deferens|tube that conveys sperm]] from the testicle to the penis\n* in males, bruising and swelling of the scrotum\n* chronic regional pain (also known as post-herniorrhaphy inguinodynia, or chronic postoperative inguinal pain)\n\n===Post-herniorraphy pain syndrome===\n[[Post herniorraphy pain syndrome|Post-herniorrhaphy inguinodynia]] is a condition where 10-12% of patients experience severe pain after inguinal hernia repair, due to a complex combination of different [[Pain|forms of pain signals]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kehlet|first=H.|date=February 2008|title=Chronic pain after groin hernia repair|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=95|issue=2|pages=135\u2013136|doi=10.1002/bjs.6111|issn=1365-2168|pmid=18196556}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Callesen|first=T.|last2=Bech|first2=K.|last3=Kehlet|first3=H.|date=December 1999|title=Prospective study of chronic pain after groin hernia repair|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=86|issue=12|pages=1528\u20131531|doi=10.1046/j.1365-2168.1999.01320.x|issn=0007-1323|pmid=10594500}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.europeanherniasociety.eu/sites/www.europeanherniasociety.eu/files/medias/PDF/HerniaSurgeGuidelinesStatementsRecomendations.pdf|title=World Guidelines for Hernia Management|website=European Hernia Society|access-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref> It can occur with any inguinal hernia repair technique, and if unresponsive to pain medications, further surgical intervention is often required.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Starling|first=J. R.|last2=Harms|first2=B. A.|last3=Schroeder|first3=M. E.|last4=Eichman|first4=P. L.|date=October 1987|title=Diagnosis and treatment of genitofemoral and ilioinguinal entrapment neuralgia|journal=Surgery|volume=102|issue=4|pages=581\u2013586|issn=0039-6060|pmid=3660235}}</ref> Removal of the implanted mesh, in combination with [[Neurectomy|bisection of regional nerves]], is commonly performed to address such cases.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aasvang|first=Eske K.|last2=Kehlet|first2=Henrik|date=February 2009|title=The effect of mesh removal and selective neurectomy on persistent postherniotomy pain|journal=Annals of Surgery|volume=249|issue=2|pages=327\u2013334|doi=10.1097/SLA.0b013e31818eec49|issn=1528-1140|pmid=19212190}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zacest|first=Andrew C.|last2=Magill|first2=Stephen T.|last3=Anderson|first3=Valerie C.|last4=Burchiel|first4=Kim J.|date=April 2010|title=Long-term outcome following ilioinguinal neurectomy for chronic pain|journal=Journal of Neurosurgery|volume=112|issue=4|pages=784\u2013789|doi=10.3171/2009.8.JNS09533|issn=1933-0693|pmid=19780646|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/f5659ef97d7a36bafde5f009e5022635954ab1fe}}</ref><ref name=\"Amid 531\u2013536\">{{Cite journal|last=Amid|first=Parviz K.|last2=Chen|first2=David C.|date=October 2011|title=Surgical treatment of chronic groin and testicular pain after laparoscopic and open preperitoneal inguinal hernia repair|journal=Journal of the American College of Surgeons|volume=213|issue=4|pages=531\u2013536|doi=10.1016/j.jamcollsurg.2011.06.424|issn=1879-1190|pmid=21784668}}</ref> There remains ongoing discussion amongst surgeons regarding the utility of planned resections of regional nerves as an attempt to prevent its occurrence.<ref name=\"Amid 531\u2013536\"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Alfieri|first=S.|last2=Amid|first2=P. K.|last3=Campanelli|first3=G.|last4=Izard|first4=G.|last5=Kehlet|first5=H.|last6=Wijsmuller|first6=A. R.|last7=Di Miceli|first7=D.|last8=Doglietto|first8=G. B.|date=June 2011|title=International guidelines for prevention and management of post-operative chronic pain following inguinal hernia surgery|journal=Hernia|volume=15|issue=3|pages=239\u2013249|doi=10.1007/s10029-011-0798-9|issn=1248-9204|pmid=21365287}}</ref>\n\n===Mortality rates===\nMortality rates for non-urgent, elective procedures was demonstrated as 0.1%, and around 3% for procedures performed urgently.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Abi-Haidar|first=Youmna|last2=Sanchez|first2=Vivian|last3=Itani|first3=Kamal M. F.|date=September 2011|title=Risk factors and outcomes of acute versus elective groin hernia surgery|journal=Journal of the American College of Surgeons|volume=213|issue=3|pages=363\u2013369|doi=10.1016/j.jamcollsurg.2011.05.008|issn=1879-1190|pmid=21680204}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> Other than urgent repair, risk factors that were also associated with increased mortality included being female, requiring a femoral hernia repair, and older age.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arenal|first=Juan J.|last2=Rodr\u00edguez-Vielba|first2=Paloma|last3=Gallo|first3=Emiliano|last4=Tinoco|first4=Claudia|date=2002|title=Hernias of the abdominal wall in patients over the age of 70 years|journal=The European Journal of Surgery = Acta Chirurgica|volume=168|issue=8\u20139|pages=460\u2013463|doi=10.1080/110241502321116451|issn=1102-4151|pmid=12549685}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Koch|first=A.|last2=Edwards|first2=A.|last3=Haapaniemi|first3=S.|last4=Nordin|first4=P.|last5=Kald|first5=A.|date=December 2005|title=Prospective evaluation of 6895 groin hernia repairs in women|journal=The British Journal of Surgery|volume=92|issue=12|pages=1553\u20131558|doi=10.1002/bjs.5156|issn=0007-1323|pmid=16187268}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dahlstrand|first=Ursula|last2=Wollert|first2=Staffan|last3=Nordin|first3=P\u00e4r|last4=Sandblom|first4=Gabriel|last5=Gunnarsson|first5=Ulf|date=April 2009|title=Emergency femoral hernia repair: a study based on a national register|journal=Annals of Surgery|volume=249|issue=4|pages=672\u2013676|doi=10.1097/SLA.0b013e31819ed943|issn=1528-1140|pmid=19300219}}</ref>\n\n== Follow-up ==\nUpon awakening from anesthesia, patients are monitored for their ability to drink fluids, produce urine, as well as their ability to walk after surgery. Most patients are then able to return home once those conditions are met.<ref name=\":422\"/> It is not uncommon for patients to experience residual soreness for a couple of days after surgery.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hewitt|first=D. Brock|last2=Chojnacki|first2=Karen|date=2017-10-03|title=Laparoscopic Groin Hernia Repair|journal=JAMA|language=en|volume=318|issue=13|pages=1294|doi=10.1001/jama.2017.11620|pmid=28973249|issn=0098-7484}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=Hewitt|first=D. Brock|last2=Chojnacki|first2=Karen|date=2017-08-22|title=Groin Hernia Repair by Open Surgery|journal=JAMA|language=en|volume=318|issue=8|pages=764|doi=10.1001/jama.2017.9868|pmid=28829878|issn=0098-7484}}</ref> Patients are encouraged to make strong efforts in getting up and walking around the day after surgery.<ref name=\":32\" /> Most patients can resume their normal routine of daily living within the week such as driving, showering, light lifting, as well as sexual activity.<ref name=\":022\"/> Long work absences are rarely necessary and length of sick days tend to be dictated by respective employment policies.<ref name=\":32\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn general, it is not recommended to administer antibiotics as prophylaxis after elective inguinal hernia repair. However, the rate of wound infection determines the appropriate use of the antibiotics.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sanchez-Manuel|first1=FJ|last2=Lozano-Garc\u00eda|first2=J|last3=Seco-Gil|first3=JL|title=Antibiotic prophylaxis for hernia repair.|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|date=15 February 2012|issue=2|pages=CD003769|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD003769.pub4|pmid=22336793}}</ref>\n\nPost-op development of any of the following should warrant timely reporting via phone:<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":422\"/>\n* fever greater than 39C/101F\n* progressive swelling of the surgical site\n* severe pain\n* recurring nausea or vomiting\n* worsening redness around incisions\n* drainage of pus from incisions\n* difficulty or lack of producing urine\n* new-onset shortness of breath\n\n== Prevention and screening ==\nMost indirect inguinal hernias in the abdominal wall are not preventable. Direct inguinal hernias may be able to be prevented by maintaining a healthy weight, refraining from smoking, preventing straining during bowel movements, and maintaining proper lifting techniques when heavy lifting.<ref name=\":422\"/><ref name=\":022\"/> There is no evidence that indicates physicians should routinely [[Screening (medicine)|screen]] for asymptomatic inguinal hernias during patient visits.<ref>DynaMed Plus [Internet]. Ipswich (MA): EBSCO Information Services. 1995 - . Record No. 113880, Groin hernia in adults and adolescents; [updated 2017 Nov 27, cited '''Nov 27, 2017''']; [about 28 screens]. Available from <nowiki>http://www.dynamed.com/login.aspx?direct=true&site=DynaMed&id=113880</nowiki>. Registration and login required.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Commons category|Inguinal hernia surgery}}\n\n{{Digestive system surgical procedures}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Inguinal Hernia Repair}}\n[[Category:Inguinal hernias]]\n[[Category:Abdominal surgical procedures]]\n[[Category:Digestive system surgery]]\n\n[[it:Chirurgia dell'ernia inguinale]]\n", "name_user": "Yash.sash", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther open mesh repair techniques", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inguinal_hernia_surgery"}
{"title_page": "Pelagius", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Undue weight|date=June 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n}}\n[[File:Pelagius from Nuremberg Chronicle.jpg|thumb|Illustration of Pelagius in the [[Nuremberg Chronicle]]]]\n\n'''Pelagius'''  ({{circa|AD&nbsp;354}}&nbsp;\u2013 418) was a [[theologian]] who advocated [[free will]] and [[asceticism]]. He was accused by [[Augustine of Hippo]] and others of denying the need for divine aid in performing [[good works]]. They understood him to have said that the only grace necessary was the declaration of the law; humans were not wounded by Adam's sin and were perfectly able to fulfill the law without divine aid. Pelagius denied Augustine's theory of [[original sin]]. Adherents of Pelagius cited [[Book of Deuteronomy|Deuteronomy]] 24:16 in support of their position. Pelagius was declared a [[heresy|heretic]] by the [[Council of Ephesus]] in 431. His interpretation of a doctrine of free will became known as [[Pelagianism]].\n\nHe was well educated, fluent in both [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] and [[Latin]], and learned in [[theology]]. He spent time as an ascetic, focusing on practical asceticism. He was well known in Rome, both for the harsh asceticism of his public life and the power and persuasiveness of his speech. His reputation earned him praise early in his career even from such pillars of the Church as Augustine, who referred to him as a \"saintly man.\" However, he was later accused of lying about his own teachings to avoid public condemnation. Most of his later life was spent defending his doctrine against Christian theologians who held that Pelagius was spreading novelties in the Faith unknown to the apostolic tradition.\n\nDue to some calling him a heretic, little of his work has come down to the present day except in the quotes of his opponents. However, more recently, some authors have defended Pelagius as a misunderstood \u201corthodox\u201d:\n{{quote|Recent analysis of his thinking suggests that it was, in fact, highly orthodox, following in the tradition established by the early fathers and in keeping with the teaching of the church in both the East and the West. ...From what we are able to piece together from the few sources available ... it seems that the [[Celts|Celtic]] monk held to an orthodox view of the prevenience of God's grace, and did not assert that individuals could achieve salvation purely by their own efforts.<ref>Bradley, Ian (1993) ''The Celtic Way''. London: Darton, Longman and Todd; p. 62</ref>|author=|title=|source=}}\n\n== Beginnings ==\nPelagius was born about 354-360. He is said by his contemporaries, such as Augustine of Hippo, [[Prosper of Aquitaine]], [[Marius Mercator]], and [[Orosius|Paul Orosius]], to have been of British origin.<ref name=DNB>{{cite encyclopedia |first=Gerald |last = Bonner|authorlink=| publisher = Oxford University Press | encyclopedia= Oxford Dictionary of National Biography| title= Pelagius (fl. c.390\u2013418), theologian| year = 2004 | url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/21784?docPos=1| accessdate=28 October 2012 |doi= 10.1093/ref:odnb/21784 }} {{ODNBsub}}</ref> [[Jerome]] apparently thought that Pelagius was Irish, suggesting that he was \"stuffed with Irish porridge\" (''Scotorum pultibus praegravatus'').<ref>Daibhi O Croinin, ''Early Medieval Ireland 400-1200'' (2013), p. 206.</ref> He was tall in stature and portly in appearance. Pelagius was also highly educated, spoke and wrote Latin and Greek with great fluency, and was well versed in theology. His name has traditionally been understood as a Graecized form (from ''p\u00e9lagos'', \"sea\") of the Welsh name Morgan (\"sea-born\"), or another Celtic equivalent.<ref>Dods, Marcus (1911). \"Pelagius\". ''The Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', vol. 21. Cambridge University Press.</ref>\n\nPelagius became better known around 380 when he moved to Rome.<ref name=Fletcher_11>{{cite book |last= Fletcher|first= Richard|title= Who's Who in Roman Britain and Anglo-Saxon England|pages=11\u201312|year= 1989|publisher= Shepheard-Walwyn|isbn=0-85683-089-5}}</ref> There he enjoyed a reputation of austerity; he also corresponded with St. [[Paulinus of Nola]].<ref name=pohle>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11604a.htm Pohle, Joseph. \"Pelagius and Pelagianism.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia. Vol. 11. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911. 18 Jan. 2014]</ref> Pelagius became concerned about the moral laxity of society. He blamed this laxity on the theology of [[divine grace]] preached by Augustine, among others. He began to teach a very strict, rigid moralism, emphasizing a natural, innate human ability to attain salvation.<ref name=Filippo>[http://www.ignatiusinsight.com/features2008/sfilippo_augustinepelag_jan08.asp Filippo, Stephen N. \"St. Augustine and Pelagianism\". ''Ignatius Insight'']</ref>\n\nWhen [[Alaric I|Alaric]] sacked Rome in 410, Pelagius and his follower [[Caelestius]] fled to [[Carthage]], where he continued his work.<ref name=Fletcher_11 /> He was in Jerusalem by 415.\n\n== Opponents ==\n[[File:Saint Augustine of Hippo.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Saint Augustine of Hippo]]]]\n\n=== Augustine of Hippo ===\nPelagianism quickly spread, especially around Carthage. Augustine wrote \"''De peccatorum meritis et remissione'' libri III\" (Three Books on the Merits and Forgiveness of Sins) in 412, and \"''De spiritu et littera''\" (On the Spirit and the Letter) in 414. When in 414 disquieting rumours arrived from Sicily and the so-called \"Definitiones Caelestii\", said to be the work of Caelestius, were sent to him, he at once (414 or 415) published the rejoinder, \"De perfectione justitiae hominis.\" In these, he strongly affirmed the existence of original sin, the need for infant baptism, the impossibility of a sinless life without Christ, and the necessity of Christ's grace. Augustine stands as an important source on the life and theology of Pelagius, and wrote about him extensively.<ref name=pohle/>\n\n=== Jerome ===\nPelagius soon left for Palestine, befriending the bishop there. Jerome, who also lived there, became involved, as well.  Pelagius had criticized his commentary on the Epistle to the Ephesians.<ref name=pohle/> Jerome wrote against Pelagius in his \"''Letter to Ctesiphon''\" and \"''Dialogus contra Pelagianos''.\" With Jerome at the time was [[Paulus Orosius|Orosius]], a visiting pupil of Augustine, with similar views on the dangers of Pelagianism. Together, they publicly condemned Pelagius. Bishop [[John II, Bishop of Jerusalem|John of Jerusalem]], a personal friend of Pelagius, called a council in July 415. Church sources claim Orosius' lack of fluency in Greek rendered him unconvincing and John's Eastern background made him more willing to accept that humans did not have inherent sinfulness, yet the council rendered no verdict and passed the controversy to the Latin Church because Pelagius, Jerome, and Orosius were all Latin.\n\n=== Diospolis ===\nA few months later in December of 415, another synod in [[Lod|Diospolis]] (Lydda) under the bishop of C\u00e6sarea was called by two deposed bishops who came to the Holy Land. However, neither bishop attended for unrelated reasons and Orosius had left after consultation with Bishop John. Pelagius explained to the synod that he did believe God was necessary for salvation because every human is created by God. He also claimed that many works of [[Celestius]] did not represent his own views. He showed letters of recommendation by other authoritative figures including Augustine himself, who for all their disagreements, thought highly of Pelagius' character.\n\nThe [[Synod of Diospolis]] therefore concluded: \"Now since we have received satisfaction in respect of the charges brought against the monk Pelagius in his presence and since he gives his assent to sound doctrines but condemns and anathematises those contrary to the faith of the Church, we adjudge him to belong to the communion of the Catholic Church.\"<ref>[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Synod_Lydda_415AD.html Jennings, Daniel R., \"Pelagius: Transcript From The Council of Diospolis (Lydda) Against Pelagius, 415AD]</ref>\n\n== Pelagius and the doctrine of free will ==\nAfter his acquittal in Diospolis, Pelagius wrote two major treatises which are no longer extant, ''On Nature'' and ''Defense of the Freedom of the Will''. In these, he defends his position on sin and sinlessness, and accuses Augustine of being under the influence of [[Manichaeism]] by elevating evil to the same status as God and teaching pagan fatalism as if it were a Christian doctrine.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nManichaeism stressed that the spirit was God-created, while material substance was corrupt and evil. Theologian Gerald Bonner felt that part of Pelagius' analysis was an over-reaction to Manicheanism. Pelagius held that everything created by God was good, therefore, he could not see how God had made humans fallen creatures.<ref>Bonner, Gerald. ''St. Augustine of Hippo: Life and Controversies'', Philadelphia: The Westminister Press, 1963</ref> (Augustine's teachings on the Fall of Adam was not a settled doctrine at the time the Augustinian/Pelagian dispute began.)\n\nThe view that mankind can avoid sinning, and that humans can freely choose to obey God's commandments, stands at the core of Pelagian teaching. Pelagius stressed human autonomy and freedom of the will.<ref name=Filippo/>\n\nAn illustration of Pelagius' views on man's \"moral ability\" not to sin can be found in his \"Letter to Demetrias\".<ref>[http://silouanthompson.net/library/early-church/pelagius-to-demetrias \"Letter of Pelagius to Demetrias\", ''The Letters of Pelagius'' (Robert Van de Weyer, ed.)]</ref> He was in the Holy Land when, in 413, he received a letter from the renowned [[Anicia (gens)|Anician]] family in Rome. One of the aristocratic ladies who had been among his followers, Anicia Juliana, was writing to a number of eminent Western theologians, including Jerome and possibly Augustine, for moral advice for her 14-year-old daughter, [[Demetrias (daughter of Anicius Hermogenianus Olybrius)|Demetrias]].  Pelagius used the letter to argue his case for morality, stressing his views of natural sanctity and man's moral capacity to choose to live a holy life.  It is perhaps the only extant writing in Pelagius' own hand, and it was thought to be a letter by Jerome for centuries, though Augustine himself references it in his work, ''On the Grace of Christ''.\n\n==Pelagius on grace==\n[[File:Pelagius.jpg|thumb|A 17th-century [[Calvinist]] print depicting Pelagius: The caption says:<br />\"Accurst Pelagius, with what false pretence<br />Durst thou excuse Man's foul Concupiscence,<br />Or cry down Sin Originall, or that<br /> The Love of GOD did Man predestinate.\"]]\nFor Pelagius, \"grace\" consisted of the gift of free will, the Law of Moses, and the teachings of Jesus.<ref>Stephen J. Duffy, Stephen J., ''The Dynamics of Grace: Perspectives in Theological Anthropology'', Collegeville, Minnesota: The Liturgical Press, 1993</ref> With these, a person would be able to perceive the moral course of action and follow it. Prayer, fasting, and asceticism supported the will to do good. Augustine accused Pelagius of thinking of God's grace as consisting only of external helps.\n\nExtant letters of Pelagius and his followers claim that all good works are done only with the grace of God (which he saw as enabling, but not forcing, good works), that infants must be baptized for salvation, and that the saints were not always sinless, but that some at least have been able to stop sinning.\n\nHe instead said, \"This grace we for our part do not, as you suppose, allow to consist merely in the law, but also in the help of God. God helps us by His teaching and revelation, whilst He opens the eyes of our heart; whilst He points out to us the future, that we may not be absorbed in the present; whilst He discovers to us the snares of the devil; whilst He enlightens us with the manifold and ineffable gift of heavenly grace.\" In a letter to the Pope defending himself, he stated, \"This free will is in all good works always assisted by divine help\", and in an accompanying confession of faith, \"Free-will we do so own, as to say that we always stand in need of God's help\", However, he affirmed that \"We do also abhor the blasphemy of those who say that any impossible thing is commanded to man by God; or that the commandments of God cannot be performed by any one man\" (a statement which the pope approved of upon receiving the letter), whereas Augustine famously stated \"''non possum non peccare''\" (\"I cannot not sin\").\n\n==Pope Innocent I ==\nIn the fall of 416, Augustine and four other bishops wrote a letter urging [[Pope Innocent I]] to condemn Pelagianism.  Innocent I responded by rejecting the Pelagian teachings and excluding Pelagius and Celestius from communion with the Catholic Church until they should recant. Shortly after this, Innocent I died in March of 417.\n\n==Pope Zosimus ==\nSeeking to undo his condemnation, Pelagius wrote a letter and statement of belief to [[Pope Zosimus]], Innocent I's successor, showing himself to be orthodox. In these he articulated his beliefs so as not to contradict what the synods condemned.  Zosimus was persuaded by Celestius to reopen the case, but opposition from the African bishops and [[Honorius (emperor)|Emperor Honorius]] forced Zosimus to condemn and excommunicate Celestius and Pelagius in 418.<ref name=DNB/>\n\nPelagianism was condemned at the [[Council of Carthage (418)|Council of Carthage in 418]].<ref name=Filippo/>  Augustine, shocked that Pelagius and Celestius were not denounced as heretics, called the Council of Carthage in 418 and stated nine beliefs of the Church that Pelagianism denied:\n\n# Death came from sin, not man's physical nature.\n# Infants must be baptized to be cleansed from original sin.\n# Justifying grace covers past sins and helps avoid future sins.\n# The grace of Christ imparts strength and will to act out God's commandments.\n# No good works can come without God's grace.\n# We confess we are sinners because it is true, not from humility.\n# The saints ask for forgiveness for their own sins.\n# The saints also confess to be sinners because they are.\n# Children dying without baptism are excluded from both the kingdom of heaven and eternal life.\n\n== Death and later ==\nAfter his condemnation, Pelagius was expelled from Jerusalem, and Saint [[Cyril of Alexandria]] allowed him to settle in Egypt. He is not heard of thereafter.<ref name=DNB/>\n\nHis death did not end his teachings, although those who followed him may have modified those teachings.  Because little information remains with regard to Pelagius' actual teachings, some of his doctrines possibly were subject to revision and suppression by his enemies (followers of Augustine and the Church leadership as a whole at that time).\n\nPelagius and Caelestius were declared heretics by the [[First Council of Ephesus]] in 431.<ref>Schaff, Philip. [http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf214.x.xvi.vii.html The Seven Ecumenical Councils: Excursus on Pelagianism], ''Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers'', series II, vol 14.</ref>\n\nBelief in Pelagianism and [[Semipelagianism]] was common for the next few centuries, especially in Britain, the Holy Land, and North Africa. [[Germanus of Auxerre|St Germanus]] visited Britain to combat Pelagianism in or around AD 429. In Wales, [[Saint David]] was credited with convening the [[Synod of Brefi]] and the [[Synod of Victory]] against the followers of Pelagius in the sixth century.\n\n==Evaluation==\nAn objective view of Pelagius and his effect is difficult. His name has been used as an epithet for centuries by both Protestants and Catholics, and he has had few defenders. The very early church denounced his ideas and the Reformation accused Roman Catholics of adhering to his beliefs and condemned both Pelagius and the Catholic Church. Modern scholarship suggests that Pelagius did not take the more extreme positions later associated with his followers.<ref name=Clark>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111006045016/http://americanphilosophy.net/pelagianheresy.htm Clark, R. Scott. \"Pelagianism\", Wheaton College, spring 1997]</ref> [[Ronald Hutton]] describes him as \"a first-rate theologian\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Pagan Britain|first=Ronald|last=Hutton|authorlink=Ronald Hutton|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven, US|year=2013|isbn=978-0-300-19771-6|page=280}}</ref>\n\n==Pelagius in literature and film==\nIn [[Hilaire Belloc]]'s ''The Four Men'', the Sailor leads his companions in the \"Song of the Pelagian Heresy for the Strengthening of Men's Backs and the very Robust Out-thrusting of Doubtful Doctrine and the Uncertain Intellectual\".\n\nPaul Morgan's novella, ''The Pelagius Book'' (2005), deals with the relationship of Pelagius, and Celestius, who in the story, is sent to spread Pelagius' teachings in Britain.<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/news/Reviews/The-Pelagius-Book/2005/06/10/1118347580857.html &nbsp; Pierce, Peter. Review of ''The Pelagius Book'', \"The Age\", June 11, 2005. Melbourne: Fairfax Digital]</ref>\n\nIn [[M J Trow]] and Richard Denham's 'Britannia' series, Pelagius is a character who has a huge moral impact on one of the four central characters, Vitalis, and his take on Christianity resonates throughout the rest of the series.\n\nPelagius is referred to in [[Stephen Lawhead]]'s book, ''The Black Rood''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lawhead |first1=Stephen R |title=The black rood |date=2000 |publisher=EOS |location=New York |isbn=9780061050343 |url=https://archive.org/details/blackrood00lawh |accessdate=19 January 2019 |language=English |url-access=registration }}</ref>, and makes an appearance in ''Patrick''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lawhead |first1=Stephen R |title=Patrick : Son of Ireland |date=2004 |publisher=HarperTorch |location=New York |isbn=9780060012823 |url=https://archive.org/details/patrick00step |accessdate=19 January 2019 |url-access=registration }}</ref>, where he has a discussion with the Hiberno-British saint.\n\nPelagius is frequently referred to in [[Jack Whyte]]'s series of books known as ''[[A Dream of Eagles]]'', where a major character's belief in Pelagius' ideas of free will and the laxity of the [[Roman Catholic]] Church eventually cause him to come into conflict with Church representatives.\n\n[[John Cowper Powys]]' novel ''[[Porius (A Romance of the Dark Ages)]]'' (1951) features the conflict between Augustinian/Pelagian beliefs, with the eponymous hero being a follower of Pelagius. Powys referred approvingly to Pelagianism in his nonfiction book ''Obstinate Cymric'' (1947).\n\nThe Saint Augustine/Pelagius debate is mockingly discussed in the novel by [[Flann O'Brien]] titled ''[[The Dalkey Archive]]'', wherein Saint Augustine actually makes a ghostly appearance.\n\nThe government of the English-speaking Union (Enspun) in [[Anthony Burgess]]' ''[[The Wanting Seed]]'' is locked in a perpetual cycle, rotating between the 'Pel-Phase', named after Pelagius, and an Augustinian phase. The former is one of police and social services; the latter is characterized by martial law. Burgess took up the Augustine/Pelagius theme again in ''[[The Clockwork Testament, or Enderby's End|The Clockwork Testament]]'' and in ''[[Earthly Powers]]''.\n\nIn the movie ''[[King Arthur (2004 film)|King Arthur]]'' (2004),<ref>[http://www.script-o-rama.com/movie_scripts/k/king-arthur-script-transcript.html \"King Arthur\"]</ref> Pelagius is a former mentor of young Lucius Artorius Castus ([[King Arthur|Arthur]]) played by Clive Owen. Arthur champions Pelagius' ideals, particularly those regarding free will. Upon learning of Pelagius's excommunication and death, Arthur realizes that the Roman ideal that he supported no longer exists.  He breaks ties with the [[Roman Empire]], and leads the [[Britons (historic)|Britons]] against the [[Saxon people|Saxon]] invaders.\n\nPelagius is the subject of a poem by the [[Glasgow]] poet [[Edwin Morgan (poet)|Edwin Morgan]] (\"Cathures\", Carcanet 2002) which imagines that Pelagius has returned to his native Glasgow (Cathures) and that his Celtic name was Morgan.\n\n[[Stephen Baxter (author)|Stephen Baxter]], in his novel ''[[Emperor (Baxter novel)|Emperor]]'', imagines how time's tapestry would have looked had Pelagius' views and not Augustine's influenced the evolution of Christianity.  He also portrays the Emperor Constantine's actions as having dealt a harsh blow, but not necessarily a mortal one, to Pelagius' teaching that humans are free and sin is not inherent in us.\n\nA facsimile of the 1808 \"A Dissertation of the Pelagian Heresy and the Refutation of it al Llandewi Brevi by St David\" has been printed in [[Carmarthen]] on the same street as the original.\n\n''Heresy: the Life of Pelagius'' (2012) by David Lovejoy, portrays Pelagius through the eyes of his (fictional) servant Arwel.<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=794693050&qt=results_page Heresy: the Life of Pelagius by David Lovejoy, Echo Publications]</ref>\n\nIn his [[Sister Fidelma mysteries|Sister Fidelma mystery series]] (1994\u2013present), author Peter Berresford Ellis, under the pen name Peter Tremayne, uses the teachings of Pelagius to contrast the dogma and practices of the contemporary Celtic church and that of Rome for supremacy in the British Isles.\n\n== Writings==\nPelagius wrote: ''De fide Trinitatis libri \u2162'' (\"On Faith in the Trinity: Three Books\"), ''Eclogarum ex divinis Scripturis liber primus'' (\"Excerpts out of Divine Scriptures: Book One\"), and ''Commentarii in epistolas S. Pauli'' (\"Commentary on the Epistles of Saint Paul\").  Unfortunately, most of his work survives only in the quotations of his opponents. Only in the past century have works attributable to Pelagius been identified as such.\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Letters.html Letters of Pelagius: To a Presbyter, Augustine of Hippo, and Pope Innocent I]\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_On_Nature.html On Nature]\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Defense_Of_The_Freedom_Of_The_Will.html Defense of the Freedom of the Will]\n* ''Pelagius's Commentary on St Paul's Epistle to the Romans''<ref>''Pelagius's Commentary on St Paul's Epistle to the Romans'' (translated with introduction and notes by Theodore de Bruyn), Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1993 {{ISBN|0-19-814399-0}}</ref>\n*''Pelagius's Expositions of the Thirteen Epistles of St. Paul''<ref>\"Pelagius's Expositions of the Thirteen Epistles of St. Paul\"  ''(edited by A. Souter) Texts and Studies; 9, 3 vols. in 1. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1922\u20131931 1: Introduction'' 2: Text \u2013 3: Pseudo-Jerome interpolations</ref>\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Chapters.html Excerpts Out of Divine Scriptures: One Book (a.k.a. Chapters)]\n*[http://seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Confession_Of_Faith.html Confession of Faith]\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Written_Anathema.html Written Anathema]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Julian of Eclanum]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Brinley Rees, ''Pelagius A Reluctant Heretic'', The Boydell Press, Woodbridge, 1988.\n* Brinley Rees (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0851157149 ''Pelagius: Life and Letters''],  The Boydell Press, Woodbridge:1989, 1991. {{ISBN|0-85115-282-1}} Translation of 18 letters, including ''Epistle to Demetrias'', and minor treatises attributed at various times to Pelagius or his followers.{{ISBN|0-85115-714-9}} \n* Robert Van de Weyer (ed.), ''The Letters of Pelagius: Celtic Soul Friend'', Little Gidding books, Evesham: Arthur James, 1995.\n* Pelagius, ''Epistula ad Demetriadem. Brief an Demetrias'', Einleitung, Edition und \u00dcbersetzung von Gisbert Greshake, [Fontes Christiani], Band 65, Herder, Freiburg, 2015\n* Squires, Stuart. The Pelagian Controversy: An Introduction to the Enemies of Grace and the Conspiracy of Lost Souls.  Eugene: Wipf and Stock, 2019.\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*{{wikisource author-inline}}\n*{{wikiquote-inline}}\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Council_Of_Carthage_May_1_418.html Canons From The Council Of Carthage Against Pelagianism, May 1, 418]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140317175252/http://www.brojed.org/pelagius.html &nbsp; Deacon Geoffrey \u00d3 Riada. ''Pelagius: To Demetrias''. An analysis of the letter and a brief biography.{{dead link|date=October 2014}}]\n*[http://www.earlychurchtexts.com/main/pelagius/pelagius_letter_to_demetrias.shtml Latin] and [http://www.earlychurchtexts.com/public/pelagius_letter_to_demetrias.htm English] versions of a short section of the letter to Demetrias.\n* {{In Our Time|The Pelagian Controversy|b010dstl|}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:418 deaths]]\n[[Category:4th-century births]]\n[[Category:5th-century Christians]]\n[[Category:5th-century Latin writers]]\n[[Category:5th-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:Ascetics]]\n[[Category:Founders of religions]]\n[[Category:Latin letter writers]]\n[[Category:People declared heretics by the first seven ecumenical councils]]\n[[Category:Romano-British Christians]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Undue weight|date=June 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n}}\n[[File:Pelagius from Nuremberg Chronicle.jpg|thumb|Illustration of Pelagius in the [[Nuremberg Chronicle]]]]\n\n'''Pelagius'''  ({{circa|AD&nbsp;354}}&nbsp;\u2013 418) was a [[theologian]] who advocated [[free will]] and [[asceticism]]. He was accused by [[Augustine of Hippo]] and others of denying the need for divine aid in performing [[good works]]. They understood him to have said that the only grace necessary was the declaration of the law; humans were not wounded by Adam's sin and were perfectly able to fulfill the law without divine aid. Pelagius denied Augustine's theory of [[original sin]]. Adherents of Pelagius cited [[Book of Deuteronomy|Deuteronomy]] 24:16 in support of their position. Pelagius was declared a [[heresy|heretic]] by the [[Council of Ephesus]] in 431. His interpretation of a doctrine of free will became known as [[Pelagianism]].\n\nHe was well educated, fluent in both [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] and [[Latin]], and learned in [[theology]]. He spent time as an ascetic, focusing on practical asceticism. He was well known in Rome, both for the harsh asceticism of his public life and the power and persuasiveness of his speech. His reputation earned him praise early in his career even from such pillars of the Church as Augustine, who referred to him as a \"saintly man.\" However, he was later accused of lying about his own teachings to avoid public condemnation. Most of his later life was spent defending his doctrine against Christian theologians who held that Pelagius was spreading novelties in the Faith unknown to the apostolic tradition.\n\nDue to some calling him a heretic, little of his work has come down to the present day except in the quotes of his opponents. However, more recently, some authors have defended Pelagius as a misunderstood \u201corthodox\u201d:\n{{quote|Recent analysis of his thinking suggests that it was, in fact, highly orthodox, following in the tradition established by the early fathers and in keeping with the teaching of the church in both the East and the West. ... From what we are able to piece together from the few sources available... it seems that the [[Celts|Celtic]] monk held to an orthodox view of the prevenience of God's grace, and did not assert that individuals could achieve salvation purely by their own efforts...<ref>Bradley, Ian (1993) ''The Celtic Way''. London: Darton, Longman and Todd; p. 62</ref>}}\n\n== Beginnings ==\nPelagius was born about 354-360. He is said by his contemporaries, such as Augustine of Hippo, [[Prosper of Aquitaine]], [[Marius Mercator]], and [[Orosius|Paul Orosius]], to have been of British origin.<ref name=DNB>{{cite encyclopedia |first=Gerald |last = Bonner|authorlink=| publisher = Oxford University Press | encyclopedia= Oxford Dictionary of National Biography| title= Pelagius (fl. c.390\u2013418), theologian| year = 2004 | url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/21784?docPos=1| accessdate=28 October 2012 |doi= 10.1093/ref:odnb/21784 }} {{ODNBsub}}</ref> [[Jerome]] apparently thought that Pelagius was Irish, suggesting that he was \"stuffed with Irish porridge\" (''Scotorum pultibus praegravatus'').<ref>Daibhi O Croinin, ''Early Medieval Ireland 400-1200'' (2013), p. 206.</ref> He was tall in stature and portly in appearance. Pelagius was also highly educated, he spoke and wrote Latin and Greek with great fluency and was well versed in theology. His name has traditionally been understood as a Graecized form (from ''p\u00e9lagos'', \"sea\") of the Welsh name Morgan (\"sea-born\"), or another Celtic equivalent.<ref>Dods, Marcus (1911). \"Pelagius\". ''The Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', vol. 21. Cambridge University Press.</ref>\n\nPelagius became better known around 380 when he moved to Rome.<ref name=Fletcher_11>{{cite book |last= Fletcher|first= Richard|title= Who's Who in Roman Britain and Anglo-Saxon England|pages=11\u201312|year= 1989|publisher= Shepheard-Walwyn|isbn=0-85683-089-5}}</ref> There he enjoyed a reputation of austerity; he also corresponded with St. [[Paulinus of Nola]].<ref name=pohle>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11604a.htm Pohle, Joseph. \"Pelagius and Pelagianism.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia. Vol. 11. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911. 18 Jan. 2014]</ref> Pelagius became concerned about the moral laxity of society. He blamed this laxity on the theology of [[divine grace]] preached by Augustine, among others. He began to teach a very strict, rigid moralism, emphasizing a natural, innate human ability to attain salvation.<ref name=Filippo>[http://www.ignatiusinsight.com/features2008/sfilippo_augustinepelag_jan08.asp Filippo, Stephen N. \"St. Augustine and Pelagianism\". ''Ignatius Insight'']</ref>\n\nWhen [[Alaric I|Alaric]] sacked Rome in 410, Pelagius and his follower [[Caelestius]] fled to [[Carthage]], where he continued his work.<ref name=Fletcher_11 /> He was in Jerusalem by 415.\n\n== Opponents ==\n[[File:Saint Augustine of Hippo.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Saint Augustine of Hippo]]]]\n\n=== Augustine of Hippo ===\nPelagianism quickly spread, especially around Carthage. Augustine wrote \"''De peccatorum meritis et remissione'' libri III\" (Three Books on the Merits and Forgiveness of Sins) in 412, and \"''De spiritu et littera''\" (On the Spirit and the Letter) in 414. When in 414 disquieting rumours arrived from Sicily and the so-called \"Definitiones Caelestii\", said to be the work of Caelestius, were sent to him, he at once (414 or 415) published the rejoinder, \"De perfectione justitiae hominis.\" In these, he strongly affirmed the existence of original sin, the need for infant baptism, the impossibility of a sinless life without Christ, and the necessity of Christ's grace. Augustine stands as an important source on the life and theology of Pelagius, and wrote about him extensively.<ref name=pohle/>\n\n=== Jerome ===\nPelagius soon left for Palestine, befriending the bishop there. Jerome, who also lived there, became involved, as well.  Pelagius had criticized his commentary on the Epistle to the Ephesians.<ref name=pohle/> Jerome wrote against Pelagius in his \"''Letter to Ctesiphon''\" and \"''Dialogus contra Pelagianos''.\" With Jerome at the time was [[Paulus Orosius|Orosius]], a visiting pupil of Augustine, with similar views on the dangers of Pelagianism. Together, they publicly condemned Pelagius. Bishop [[John II, Bishop of Jerusalem|John of Jerusalem]], a personal friend of Pelagius, called a council in July 415. Church sources claim Orosius' lack of fluency in Greek rendered him unconvincing and John's Eastern background made him more willing to accept that humans did not have inherent sinfulness, yet the council rendered no verdict and passed the controversy to the Latin Church because Pelagius, Jerome, and Orosius were all Latin.\n\n=== Diospolis ===\nA few months later in December of 415, another synod in [[Lod|Diospolis]] (Lydda) under the bishop of C\u00e6sarea was called by two deposed bishops who came to the Holy Land. However, neither bishop attended for unrelated reasons and Orosius had left after consultation with Bishop John. Pelagius explained to the synod that he did believe God was necessary for salvation because every human is created by God. He also claimed that many works of [[Celestius]] did not represent his own views. He showed letters of recommendation by other authoritative figures including Augustine himself, who for all their disagreements, thought highly of Pelagius' character.\n\nThe [[Synod of Diospolis]] therefore concluded: \"Now since we have received satisfaction in respect of the charges brought against the monk Pelagius in his presence and since he gives his assent to sound doctrines but condemns and anathematises those contrary to the faith of the Church, we adjudge him to belong to the communion of the Catholic Church.\"<ref>[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Synod_Lydda_415AD.html Jennings, Daniel R., \"Pelagius: Transcript From The Council of Diospolis (Lydda) Against Pelagius, 415AD]</ref>\n\n== Pelagius and the doctrine of free will ==\nAfter his acquittal in Diospolis, Pelagius wrote two major treatises which are no longer extant, ''On Nature'' and ''Defense of the Freedom of the Will''. In these, he defends his position on sin and sinlessness, and accuses Augustine of being under the influence of [[Manichaeism]] by elevating evil to the same status as God and teaching pagan fatalism as if it were a Christian doctrine.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nManichaeism stressed that the spirit was God-created, while material substance was corrupt and evil. Theologian Gerald Bonner felt that part of Pelagius' analysis was an over-reaction to Manicheanism. Pelagius held that everything created by God was good, therefore, he could not see how God had made humans fallen creatures.<ref>Bonner, Gerald. ''St. Augustine of Hippo: Life and Controversies'', Philadelphia: The Westminister Press, 1963</ref> (Augustine's teachings on the Fall of Adam was not a settled doctrine at the time the Augustinian/Pelagian dispute began.)\n\nThe view that mankind can avoid sinning, and that humans can freely choose to obey God's commandments, stands at the core of Pelagian teaching. Pelagius stressed human autonomy and freedom of the will.<ref name=Filippo/>\n\nAn illustration of Pelagius' views on man's \"moral ability\" not to sin can be found in his \"Letter to Demetrias\".<ref>[http://silouanthompson.net/library/early-church/pelagius-to-demetrias \"Letter of Pelagius to Demetrias\", ''The Letters of Pelagius'' (Robert Van de Weyer, ed.)]</ref> He was in the Holy Land when, in 413, he received a letter from the renowned [[Anicia (gens)|Anician]] family in Rome. One of the aristocratic ladies who had been among his followers, Anicia Juliana, was writing to a number of eminent Western theologians, including Jerome and possibly Augustine, for moral advice for her 14-year-old daughter, [[Demetrias (daughter of Anicius Hermogenianus Olybrius)|Demetrias]].  Pelagius used the letter to argue his case for morality, stressing his views of natural sanctity and man's moral capacity to choose to live a holy life.  It is perhaps the only extant writing in Pelagius' own hand, and it was thought to be a letter by Jerome for centuries, though Augustine himself references it in his work, ''On the Grace of Christ''.\n\n==Pelagius on grace==\n[[File:Pelagius.jpg|thumb|A 17th-century [[Calvinist]] print depicting Pelagius: The caption says:<br />\"Accurst Pelagius, with what false pretence<br />Durst thou excuse Man's foul Concupiscence,<br />Or cry down Sin Originall, or that<br /> The Love of GOD did Man predestinate.\"]]\nFor Pelagius, \"grace\" consisted of the gift of free will, the Law of Moses, and the teachings of Jesus.<ref>Stephen J. Duffy, Stephen J., ''The Dynamics of Grace: Perspectives in Theological Anthropology'', Collegeville, Minnesota: The Liturgical Press, 1993</ref> With these, a person would be able to perceive the moral course of action and follow it. Prayer, fasting, and asceticism supported the will to do good. Augustine accused Pelagius of thinking of God's grace as consisting only of external helps.\n\nExtant letters of Pelagius and his followers claim that all good works are done only with the grace of God (which he saw as enabling, but not forcing, good works), that infants must be baptized for salvation, and that the saints were not always sinless, but that some at least have been able to stop sinning.\n\nHe instead said, \"This grace we for our part do not, as you suppose, allow to consist merely in the law, but also in the help of God. God helps us by His teaching and revelation, whilst He opens the eyes of our heart; whilst He points out to us the future, that we may not be absorbed in the present; whilst He discovers to us the snares of the devil; whilst He enlightens us with the manifold and ineffable gift of heavenly grace.\" In a letter to the Pope defending himself, he stated, \"This free will is in all good works always assisted by divine help\", and in an accompanying confession of faith, \"Free-will we do so own, as to say that we always stand in need of God's help\", However, he affirmed that \"We do also abhor the blasphemy of those who say that any impossible thing is commanded to man by God; or that the commandments of God cannot be performed by any one man\" (a statement which the pope approved of upon receiving the letter), whereas Augustine famously stated \"''non possum non peccare''\" (\"I cannot not sin\").\n\n==Pope Innocent I ==\nIn the fall of 416, Augustine and four other bishops wrote a letter urging [[Pope Innocent I]] to condemn Pelagianism.  Innocent I responded by rejecting the Pelagian teachings and excluding Pelagius and Celestius from communion with the Catholic Church until they should recant. Shortly after this, Innocent I died in March of 417.\n\n==Pope Zosimus ==\nSeeking to undo his condemnation, Pelagius wrote a letter and statement of belief to [[Pope Zosimus]], Innocent I's successor, showing himself to be orthodox. In these he articulated his beliefs so as not to contradict what the synods condemned.  Zosimus was persuaded by Celestius to reopen the case, but opposition from the African bishops and [[Honorius (emperor)|Emperor Honorius]] forced Zosimus to condemn and excommunicate Celestius and Pelagius in 418.<ref name=DNB/>\n\nPelagianism was condemned at the [[Council of Carthage (418)|Council of Carthage in 418]].<ref name=Filippo/>  Augustine, shocked that Pelagius and Celestius were not denounced as heretics, called the Council of Carthage in 418 and stated nine beliefs of the Church that Pelagianism denied:\n\n# Death came from sin, not man's physical nature.\n# Infants must be baptized to be cleansed from original sin.\n# Justifying grace covers past sins and helps avoid future sins.\n# The grace of Christ imparts strength and will to act out God's commandments.\n# No good works can come without God's grace.\n# We confess we are sinners because it is true, not from humility.\n# The saints ask for forgiveness for their own sins.\n# The saints also confess to be sinners because they are.\n# Children dying without baptism are excluded from both the kingdom of heaven and eternal life.\n\n== Death and later ==\nAfter his condemnation, Pelagius was expelled from Jerusalem, and Saint [[Cyril of Alexandria]] allowed him to settle in Egypt. He is not heard of thereafter.<ref name=DNB/>\n\nHis death did not end his teachings, although those who followed him may have modified those teachings.  Because little information remains with regard to Pelagius' actual teachings, some of his doctrines possibly were subject to revision and suppression by his enemies (followers of Augustine and the Church leadership as a whole at that time).\n\nPelagius and Caelestius were declared heretics by the [[First Council of Ephesus]] in 431.<ref>Schaff, Philip. [http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf214.x.xvi.vii.html The Seven Ecumenical Councils: Excursus on Pelagianism], ''Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers'', series II, vol 14.</ref>\n\nBelief in Pelagianism and [[Semipelagianism]] was common for the next few centuries, especially in Britain, the Holy Land, and North Africa. [[Germanus of Auxerre|St Germanus]] visited Britain to combat Pelagianism in or around AD 429. In Wales, [[Saint David]] was credited with convening the [[Synod of Brefi]] and the [[Synod of Victory]] against the followers of Pelagius in the sixth century.\n\n==Evaluation==\nAn objective view of Pelagius and his effect is difficult. His name has been used as an epithet for centuries by both Protestants and Catholics, and he has had few defenders. The very early church denounced his ideas and the Reformation accused Roman Catholics of adhering to his beliefs and condemned both Pelagius and the Catholic Church. Modern scholarship suggests that Pelagius did not take the more extreme positions later associated with his followers.<ref name=Clark>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111006045016/http://americanphilosophy.net/pelagianheresy.htm Clark, R. Scott. \"Pelagianism\", Wheaton College, spring 1997]</ref> [[Ronald Hutton]] describes him as \"a first-rate theologian\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Pagan Britain|first=Ronald|last=Hutton|authorlink=Ronald Hutton|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven, US|year=2013|isbn=978-0-300-19771-6|page=280}}</ref>\n\n==Pelagius in literature and film==\nIn [[Hilaire Belloc]]'s ''The Four Men'', the Sailor leads his companions in the \"Song of the Pelagian Heresy for the Strengthening of Men's Backs and the very Robust Out-thrusting of Doubtful Doctrine and the Uncertain Intellectual\".\n\nPaul Morgan's novella, ''The Pelagius Book'' (2005), deals with the relationship of Pelagius, and Celestius, who in the story, is sent to spread Pelagius' teachings in Britain.<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/news/Reviews/The-Pelagius-Book/2005/06/10/1118347580857.html &nbsp; Pierce, Peter. Review of ''The Pelagius Book'', \"The Age\", June 11, 2005. Melbourne: Fairfax Digital]</ref>\n\nIn [[M J Trow]] and Richard Denham's 'Britannia' series, Pelagius is a character who has a huge moral impact on one of the four central characters, Vitalis, and his take on Christianity resonates throughout the rest of the series.\n\nPelagius is referred to in [[Stephen Lawhead]]'s book, ''The Black Rood''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lawhead |first1=Stephen R |title=The black rood |date=2000 |publisher=EOS |location=New York |isbn=9780061050343 |url=https://archive.org/details/blackrood00lawh |accessdate=19 January 2019 |language=English |url-access=registration }}</ref>, and makes an appearance in ''Patrick''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lawhead |first1=Stephen R |title=Patrick : Son of Ireland |date=2004 |publisher=HarperTorch |location=New York |isbn=9780060012823 |url=https://archive.org/details/patrick00step |accessdate=19 January 2019 |url-access=registration }}</ref>, where he has a discussion with the Hiberno-British saint.\n\nPelagius is frequently referred to in [[Jack Whyte]]'s series of books known as ''[[A Dream of Eagles]]'', where a major character's belief in Pelagius' ideas of free will and the laxity of the [[Roman Catholic]] Church eventually cause him to come into conflict with Church representatives.\n\n[[John Cowper Powys]]' novel ''[[Porius (A Romance of the Dark Ages)]]'' (1951) features the conflict between Augustinian/Pelagian beliefs, with the eponymous hero being a follower of Pelagius. Powys referred approvingly to Pelagianism in his nonfiction book ''Obstinate Cymric'' (1947).\n\nThe Saint Augustine/Pelagius debate is mockingly discussed in the novel by [[Flann O'Brien]] titled ''[[The Dalkey Archive]]'', wherein Saint Augustine actually makes a ghostly appearance.\n\nThe government of the English-speaking Union (Enspun) in [[Anthony Burgess]]' ''[[The Wanting Seed]]'' is locked in a perpetual cycle, rotating between the 'Pel-Phase', named after Pelagius, and an Augustinian phase. The former is one of police and social services; the latter is characterized by martial law. Burgess took up the Augustine/Pelagius theme again in ''[[The Clockwork Testament, or Enderby's End|The Clockwork Testament]]'' and in ''[[Earthly Powers]]''.\n\nIn the movie ''[[King Arthur (2004 film)|King Arthur]]'' (2004),<ref>[http://www.script-o-rama.com/movie_scripts/k/king-arthur-script-transcript.html \"King Arthur\"]</ref> Pelagius is a former mentor of young Lucius Artorius Castus ([[King Arthur|Arthur]]) played by Clive Owen. Arthur champions Pelagius' ideals, particularly those regarding free will. Upon learning of Pelagius's excommunication and death, Arthur realizes that the Roman ideal that he supported no longer exists.  He breaks ties with the [[Roman Empire]], and leads the [[Britons (historic)|Britons]] against the [[Saxon people|Saxon]] invaders.\n\nPelagius is the subject of a poem by the [[Glasgow]] poet [[Edwin Morgan (poet)|Edwin Morgan]] (\"Cathures\", Carcanet 2002) which imagines that Pelagius has returned to his native Glasgow (Cathures) and that his Celtic name was Morgan.\n\n[[Stephen Baxter (author)|Stephen Baxter]], in his novel ''[[Emperor (Baxter novel)|Emperor]]'', imagines how time's tapestry would have looked had Pelagius' views and not Augustine's influenced the evolution of Christianity.  He also portrays the Emperor Constantine's actions as having dealt a harsh blow, but not necessarily a mortal one, to Pelagius' teaching that humans are free and sin is not inherent in us.\n\nA facsimile of the 1808 \"A Dissertation of the Pelagian Heresy and the Refutation of it al Llandewi Brevi by St David\" has been printed in [[Carmarthen]] on the same street as the original.\n\n''Heresy: the Life of Pelagius'' (2012) by David Lovejoy, portrays Pelagius through the eyes of his (fictional) servant Arwel.<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=794693050&qt=results_page Heresy: the Life of Pelagius by David Lovejoy, Echo Publications]</ref>\n\nIn his [[Sister Fidelma mysteries|Sister Fidelma mystery series]] (1994\u2013present), author Peter Berresford Ellis, under the pen name Peter Tremayne, uses the teachings of Pelagius to contrast the dogma and practices of the contemporary Celtic church and that of Rome for supremacy in the British Isles.\n\n== Writings==\nPelagius wrote: ''De fide Trinitatis libri \u2162'' (\"On Faith in the Trinity: Three Books\"), ''Eclogarum ex divinis Scripturis liber primus'' (\"Excerpts out of Divine Scriptures: Book One\"), and ''Commentarii in epistolas S. Pauli'' (\"Commentary on the Epistles of Saint Paul\").  Unfortunately, most of his work survives only in the quotations of his opponents. Only in the past century have works attributable to Pelagius been identified as such.\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Letters.html Letters of Pelagius: To a Presbyter, Augustine of Hippo, and Pope Innocent I]\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_On_Nature.html On Nature]\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Defense_Of_The_Freedom_Of_The_Will.html Defense of the Freedom of the Will]\n* ''Pelagius's Commentary on St Paul's Epistle to the Romans''<ref>''Pelagius's Commentary on St Paul's Epistle to the Romans'' (translated with introduction and notes by Theodore de Bruyn), Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1993 {{ISBN|0-19-814399-0}}</ref>\n*''Pelagius's Expositions of the Thirteen Epistles of St. Paul''<ref>\"Pelagius's Expositions of the Thirteen Epistles of St. Paul\"  ''(edited by A. Souter) Texts and Studies; 9, 3 vols. in 1. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1922\u20131931 1: Introduction'' 2: Text \u2013 3: Pseudo-Jerome interpolations</ref>\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Chapters.html Excerpts Out of Divine Scriptures: One Book (a.k.a. Chapters)]\n*[http://seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Confession_Of_Faith.html Confession of Faith]\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Written_Anathema.html Written Anathema]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Julian of Eclanum]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Brinley Rees, ''Pelagius A Reluctant Heretic'', The Boydell Press, Woodbridge, 1988.\n* Brinley Rees (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0851157149 ''Pelagius: Life and Letters''],  The Boydell Press, Woodbridge:1989, 1991. {{ISBN|0-85115-282-1}} Translation of 18 letters, including ''Epistle to Demetrias'', and minor treatises attributed at various times to Pelagius or his followers.{{ISBN|0-85115-714-9}} \n* Robert Van de Weyer (ed.), ''The Letters of Pelagius: Celtic Soul Friend'', Little Gidding books, Evesham: Arthur James, 1995.\n* Pelagius, ''Epistula ad Demetriadem. Brief an Demetrias'', Einleitung, Edition und \u00dcbersetzung von Gisbert Greshake, [Fontes Christiani], Band 65, Herder, Freiburg, 2015\n* Squires, Stuart. The Pelagian Controversy: An Introduction to the Enemies of Grace and the Conspiracy of Lost Souls.  Eugene: Wipf and Stock, 2019.\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*{{wikisource author-inline}}\n*{{wikiquote-inline}}\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Council_Of_Carthage_May_1_418.html Canons From The Council Of Carthage Against Pelagianism, May 1, 418]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140317175252/http://www.brojed.org/pelagius.html &nbsp; Deacon Geoffrey \u00d3 Riada. ''Pelagius: To Demetrias''. An analysis of the letter and a brief biography.{{dead link|date=October 2014}}]\n*[http://www.earlychurchtexts.com/main/pelagius/pelagius_letter_to_demetrias.shtml Latin] and [ht